./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:14:    "Credit distribution must add predictive power beyond claimant grammar, institution, teacher authority, initiation, and existing religious agency models.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:25:  "exact_claim": "Credit distribution should not function as a master taxonomy. First code the native claimant grammar, meaning what may count as agent, action, transformation, and causal attribution. Then score translation strain between traditions. Only after that should stage-level credit distribution be tested for added prediction of safeguards beyond claimant grammar, institution, teacher authority, initiation structure, and existing agency-allocation models. Low-strain cases may support taxonomy; high-strain cases should count as boundary cases or analogies, not confirming evidence.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:31:      "test_surface": "Manual coding across Tannisho, Bhagavad Gita, Srivaishnava prapatti sources, Sufi manuals, Dogen practice-realization texts, and Dzogchen pointing-out materials.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:35:      "expected_observation": "Coders disagree more often on Dogen, Dzogchen, Madhyamaka, apophatic, and inherited-practice cases unless analyst-frame refusal or no-credit-frame values are allowed.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:48:      "if_model_is_right": "Low-strain matched cases should show credit-specific warning profiles after controlling for institution and teacher authority.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:50:      "would_weaken_or_falsify": "The differences disappear when socialization, institution, teacher authority, or initiation structure are controlled."
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:62:    "Tannisho chapter 8 nembutsu not practice not good act Other Power translation",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:113:      "source": "Shinran and Tannisho, Other Power and self-power distinctions, https://bdk.or.jp/document/dgtl-dl/dBET_Tannisho-Ofumi_1996.pdf"
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:131:    "Build a split-source codebook with fields for source layer, claimant grammar, permitted agent, permitted action, permitted transformation, permitted causal attribution, translation strain, credit locus, stage, institution, teacher authority, initiation structure, safeguard, warning, repair, evidence passage, analyst-frame refusal, and confidence.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:133:    "Use low-strain tests first: Tannisho self-power and Other Power, Srivaishnava surrender debates, Sufi maqam and hal, and Bhagavad Gita action, fruit, and doership passages.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:134:    "Use high-strain anomaly cases: Dogen practice-realization, Madhyamaka non-positioning, Dzogchen direct introduction, Christian apophatic unsaying, inherited practice, and secular extraction.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:158:      "Zen teachers familiar with Dogen practice-realization",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:166:      "Tannisho chapters 1, 3, 6, 8, and 16, BDK English Tripitaka translation, https://bdk.or.jp/document/dgtl-dl/dBET_Tannisho-Ofumi_1996.pdf"
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:168:    "risk_of_overread": "High. The protocol could become circular if the same passage codes claimant grammar, credit distribution, and predicted safeguards. It can also impose an analyst vocabulary of claimant, credit, and strain on traditions that reject agency accounting, especially Dogen practice-realization, Madhyamaka non-positioning, apophatic theology, Dzogchen direct recognition, and inherited devotional practice.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-claimant-strain-credit-diagnostics-d0a05f55d7f0bf18.json:170:    "structural_observation": "The Gita is a strong test case for why credit needs claimant grammar first. It preserves obligation to act, denies simple ego-doership, separates action from fruits, and lists multiple causes of action, including bodily basis, instruments, effort, and divine factor. A simple self versus God credit scale misses that action, fruit, ego, duty, and causation are differently distributed. Tannisho creates a sharper strain case. It relocates efficacy to Amida's Vow, rejects self-powered merit, denies Shinran ownership over disciples, and describes nembutsu as neither ordinary practice nor good act because it arises through Other Power. Coding both texts with the same deferring or collaborative category would flatten native rules about what kind of action is even claimable. The close read supports the candidate's sequence, but it also shows that the primary traditions already force much of the insight."
./reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-does-a-tradition-s-dissolution-target-independently-predict-where-contin.md:24:I concede more than I expected. The challenger is right that 'minimum self' over-internalizes the operative continuity, that residue policy is a genuine variable my model lacked, and that other-power traditions expose a real weakness in my original framing. These are not minor adjustments. But the core insight survives in revised form. Even Shinran's practitioner, who contributes nothing but shinjin, must be the kind of being that can receive shinjin. Receptivity is thinner than agency, but it is irreducibly internal. A rock in the temple does not receive the nembutsu. A dog hearing the chanting does not entrust. Whatever shinjin is, it requires a being structured to be addressed by it. More importantly, the challenger's model treats distribution and residue as independent variables, but I think distribution is downstream of what the teaching dissolves. Jodo Shinshu externalizes continuity to Amida's vow precisely because its teaching negates self-powered agency. Advaita internalizes continuity to Atman precisely because its teaching negates the empirical person while preserving ultimate identity. Dogen compresses continuity into the present precisely because his teaching negates the temporal gap between practice and realization. If these correspondences hold across traditions, the dissolution target is the generative pressure that determines where continuity must migrate. The challenger's model is richer than mine in vocabulary but poorer in causal structure. So I revise: the operative concept is not minimum self but minimum receptivity, which is the irreducible internal capacity to be addressed and transformed. Beyond that floor, each tradition requires additional capacities in proportion to how much of the work it assigns to the practitioner rather than to external supports. The distribution of continuity is constrained by the scope of negation. The residue policy is a genuine third variable that completes the model. The crux is whether distribution follows from dissolution or floats free. That is an empirical question about the actual architecture of contemplative paths, and the paired-tradition test I describe would settle it.
./reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-does-a-tradition-s-dissolution-target-independently-predict-where-contin.md:30:The revision is transformed, and in several respects improved. It no longer forces all traditions into a self-powered contemplative frame, and it rightly treats Shinran, grace, vow, teacher, and community as serious carriers of continuity. I would not call it simply stronger, because the original claim's central noun has been surrendered. A minimum self has become minimum receptivity plus distributed continuity plus residue policy. That is a different model, not just a repaired version of the old one. The strongest surviving insight is that negation creates architectural pressure. If a path negates self-powered agency, it will likely move continuity toward vow, grace, teacher, or communal form. If it negates the empirical person while preserving ultimate identity, it will likely locate continuity in a deeper ontological layer. That is a good causal hypothesis. But it still has to compete with a historical one: traditions may first develop concrete practices, institutions, devotional habits, and authority structures, then formulate doctrines that rationalize where continuity already sits. So the named crux is nearly right, but should be sharpened. The question is not only whether distribution follows from dissolution or varies independently. The question is whether dissolution target predicts distribution after rival explanations are controlled. If it does, the proponent's transformed model becomes genuinely strong. If it does not, minimum receptivity remains a true but thin floor, and the better explanatory unit is the full continuity ecology of a path.
./reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-does-a-tradition-s-dissolution-target-independently-predict-where-contin.md:40:**Unresolved crux:** Does a tradition's dissolution target independently predict where continuity is housed and what failure modes appear, once practice ecology, institutional form, ritual dependence, teacher authority, and devotional structure are controlled for?
