./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-transfer-profile-formal-boundaries-and-dissolution-gradients-in-contemplative-practice-92ca8dca94e1acc0.json:72:      "overlap": "Very close for the gradient claim. The text distinguishes abandoned self-view from residual I-am conceit and describes later uprooting through further practice.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-transfer-profile-formal-boundaries-and-dissolution-gradients-in-contemplative-practice-92ca8dca94e1acc0.json:79:      "source": "Tannisho, Unno translation, https://www.themathesontrust.org/papers/fareasternreligions/Tannisho-Unno.pdf; Shinran Notes, https://shinranworks.com/commentaries/notes-on-once-calling-and-many-calling/"
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-transfer-profile-formal-boundaries-and-dissolution-gradients-in-contemplative-practice-92ca8dca94e1acc0.json:94:      "difference": "The candidate can handle Dogen only if it allows no-boundary and analyst-frame-refused values.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-transfer-profile-formal-boundaries-and-dissolution-gradients-in-contemplative-practice-92ca8dca94e1acc0.json:97:      "source": "Dogen, Bendowa practice-realization, https://buddhismnow.com/2023/10/08/practice-within-realisation-dogen/"
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-transfer-profile-formal-boundaries-and-dissolution-gradients-in-contemplative-practice-92ca8dca94e1acc0.json:172:      "Tannisho, Taitetsu Unno translation, https://www.themathesontrust.org/papers/fareasternreligions/Tannisho-Unno.pdf",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-transfer-profile-formal-boundaries-and-dissolution-gradients-in-contemplative-practice-92ca8dca94e1acc0.json:177:    "structural_observation": "SN 22.89 already separates a formal path achievement from a remaining gradient: the noble disciple has abandoned lower fetters and does not assume 'I am this,' yet residual 'I am' conceit, desire, and obsession remain until further contemplation uproots them. SN 45.8 gives a clear practitioner-agency grammar for right effort. Tannisho gives the opposite formal marker: entrusting, non-calculation, and Amida's working, while warning against claiming nembutsu as one's own practice. Cross-reading these texts supports the candidate's two-track architecture, but also shows that much of the architecture is already available in primary sources."
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-transfer-profile-formal-boundaries-and-dissolution-gradients-in-contemplative-practice-92ca8dca94e1acc0.json:186:  "unlike_statement": "Unlike Khemaka, Shinran, Dzogchen instructions, Dogen, Pargament, Bein, Trungpa, VCE, and prior Lumenary ledgers, this idea says the comparative unit is a two-track transfer profile and predicts that safeguards cluster where formal agency grammar changes while partial dissolution leaves layer-specific reappropriation risks."
./reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-does-scaffold-location-combined-with-practice-load-and-containment-quali.md:18:**Steelman:** The proponent is not merely saying that no-self traditions secretly need an ego. The stronger claim is architectural: any path that asks a practitioner to dissolve, transcend, or radically reframe selfhood must still preserve enough hearing, memory, continuity, error recognition, and responsiveness for the path to operate. The value of the model is comparative, because different traditions solve this operating requirement differently: causal continuity in Buddhist no-self, recognition of the already-present Self in Advaita, practice-realization in Dogen, divine restoration in fana and baqa. If this variable predicts training sequence, warnings, verification, and characteristic failures, it is a useful Lumenary model even where the metaphysics remain incompatible.
./reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-does-scaffold-location-combined-with-practice-load-and-containment-quali.md:24:The challenger's scaffold-location model is a genuine improvement, and I accept it as a generalization of the original minimum-self claim. But generalization is not replacement. The minimum-self tension survives as the sharpest special case within the scaffold model: the case where the path locates its operating requirements inside the practitioner's own agency and simultaneously teaches that this agency is groundless. Pure Land, guru-yoga, and grace traditions face a softer version of this tension because they distribute continuity across relational, institutional, and divine structures. But even Shinran, the most radical proponent of Other Power, could not fully externalize the scaffold. The Tannisho records his anguish about whether his entrusting is genuine or calculated; the Kyogyoshinsho insists that shinjin is received, not achieved, yet acknowledges that hearing is a necessary condition for reception. The capacity to hear and be turned persists as a residual intrapersonal requirement even in the most externalized scaffold. The modern relevance is not metaphysical but clinical. People drawn to self-transcending practices today often arrive shaped by conditions that weaken self-coherence: trauma, dissociation, chronic shame, achievement-contingent identity, the particular modern pressure of performing a self under constant digital comparison while feeling that the performed self is empty. For this cohort, the scaffold-location variable is not a philosophical nicety; it is a harm-prediction tool. Paths that locate the scaffold intrapersonally (sustained solo attention, unsupported intensive retreat) without adequate external support are more dangerous for scaffold-fragile practitioners than paths that distribute continuity across teacher, community, ritual, and embodied routine. The prediction: adverse outcomes from self-dissolution practices should correlate with scaffold-poverty, meaning the combination of intrapersonal scaffold demand and minimal external support. This is testable through teacher screening practices, adverse event reports, and practitioner outcome data. The non-fit case sharpens the claim: someone whose suffering is not excess self but fragmented self is not served by the minimum-self model as a path recommendation. They are served by it as a warning system. And the warning is scaffold-specific: the same person harmed by ten days of silent solo vipassana might be well supported by a Pure Land community, a Sufi circle with a living murshid, or a monastic sangha with daily embodied structure. The model's value is not in telling people what selfhood is, but in predicting where the supports need to be when selfhood is being worked on.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-28-a-practice-cannot-name-itself-df9d5fed41c6e168.json:50:    "\"discursive tradition\" \"correct form and purpose\" Asad practice authority",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-28-a-practice-cannot-name-itself-df9d5fed41c6e168.json:91:    "Build a recognition-ecology coding sheet with fields for method, claimed shift, naming authority, correction authority, unsafe authority, no-authority, interpretation stability, warning, repair, and ordinary conduct.",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-28-a-practice-cannot-name-itself-df9d5fed41c6e168.json:115:      "MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta, Thanissaro Bhikkhu translation, https://www.accesstoinsight.org/tipitaka/mn/mn.022.than.html",
./reviews/originality/2026-05-28-a-practice-cannot-name-itself-df9d5fed41c6e168.json:116:      "Dogen, Bendowa, practice-realization material as presented by Everyday Zen Foundation, https://everydayzen.org/teachings/dogens-bendowa-part-2-of-3/"
./reviews/originality/2026-05-28-a-practice-cannot-name-itself-df9d5fed41c6e168.json:120:    "structural_observation": "MN 22 does not leave Arittha's interpretation to private experience. The community reports the misreading, the Buddha cross-examines it, and the raft simile then teaches right use and release of the Dhamma. The method is not self-naming because wrong grasp is corrected by teacher and sangha. Bendowa strains the model. Dogen collapses practice and realization so strongly that there is no simple later event to label, yet the text still frames zazen through transmitted Buddha-dharma, trust, and instruction. The comparison supports the recognition claim, but it also shows the claim is already native to many practice ecologies rather than newly discovered."
