./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice-e59e1c607fa2dc18.md:27:- Tannisho sections I to X, https://nembutsu.cc/buddhism/the-tannisho/tannisho-sections-i-to-x/
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice-e59e1c607fa2dc18.md:30:Structural observation: The primary texts support distribution of direction, but they also reduce novelty. MN 10 does not present bare neutral attention, it gives frames, ardency, hindrance work, aggregate analysis, arising, and disappearance. Vivekachudamani directs the seeker from the start through discrimination, dispassion, teacher relation, and self-knowledge. Tannisho relocates decisive efficacy away from self-owned practice into entrusting and Other Power, even calling nembutsu non-practice and non-good from the practicer's side. Longchenpa's Trekcho instruction moves through preliminary deconstruction, teacher introduction, recognition of rigpa, and sustaining without effort or clinging. This close read supports the model's layer claim, but the structures are already visible in the sources themselves.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice-e59e1c607fa2dc18.md:34:Risk of overread: High. The model can become too absorbent if every difference is assigned to some layer after the fact. Tannisho and radical Other Power traditions can reject the analyst's practice-direction frame. Dogen-style practice-realization can collapse means and result. Bahiya-style immediacy strains any developmental layer sequence. Community, doctrine, teacher style, clinical risk, and social belonging may explain many cases without this model.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice-e59e1c607fa2dc18.md:47:- Tannisho non-practice non-good Other Power primary text
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice-e59e1c607fa2dc18.md:57:- Bourdieu and Wacquant on habitus and hysteresis, Wacquant abstract, https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/1357034X13501348: overlap: Close for embodied grain and switching difficulty. Habitus names durable cognitive, conative, affective, and bodily dispositions; hysteresis names mismatch when dispositions meet a changed field.; difference: This source does not distinguish lexical, attentional, devotional, teacher, and post-insight direction in contemplative traditions.; novelty impact: High reduction for embodied grain and transfer resistance.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice-e59e1c607fa2dc18.md:69:Candidate: Bahiya's immediate release, Tannisho's non-practice Other Power, and Dogen's practice-realization collapse the model's tendency to locate direction in analyzable layers.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice-e59e1c607fa2dc18.md:71:Why it strains the model: Bahiya receives a brief instruction and is said to be released immediately, so textual coding cannot show whether direction came from prior training, readiness, teacher authority, or the instruction itself. Tannisho denies self-owned practice calculation and assigns decisive efficacy to Other Power, so calling nembutsu a directed practice can distort the source. Dogen-style practice-realization refuses a clean sequence of practice first and result later, so layer location may be an analyst imposition.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice-e59e1c607fa2dc18.md:77:- If: If direction layers have real explanatory force, split-source blind coders should infer warning and repair profiles from entry or instruction texts before reading manuals or interviews. Then: Layer scores should predict held-out warnings and repairs above baselines using tradition name, technique family, teacher style, social ecology, Pargament agency style, Lutz matrix dimensions, and VCE factors. Weakens if: Low inter-rater reliability, no predictive lift, or equally strong predictions from simpler baselines would weaken the model. Test surface: Six-case corpus: MN 10, Vivekachudamani, Tannisho, Bendowa or Genjokoan, a Dzogchen or Mahamudra pointing-out manual, and The Cloud of Unknowing.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice-e59e1c607fa2dc18.md:79:- If: If framing and authorization are independent layers, the same attentional operation should produce different outcomes when embedded in different lexical, devotional, teacher, or community frames. Then: Matched instructions with identical attentional operations but different stated aim, authority, and integration rule should yield different reports of agency, effort, trust, self-reification, and repair needs. Weakens if: No measurable difference between differently framed versions, after controlling for expectancy and teacher effects, would weaken the layer claim. Test surface: Ethically low-risk short-practice experiments with experienced practitioners, not vulnerable beginners.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice-e59e1c607fa2dc18.md:112:Structural translation: Therapeutic systems also place change-direction in layers: case-formulation vocabulary, bodily routine, affective posture, intervention operation, therapist authority, supervision community, and post-session integration.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice-e59e1c607fa2dc18.md:114:Prediction: Clients or trainees switching from CBT to psychodynamic, ACT, IFS, somatic, or exposure-based work should show layer-specific transfer effects. Old formulation vocabulary, effort style, authority relation, or integration habits should predict predictable stuck points and repair instructions.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-layered-direction-of-practice-e59e1c607fa2dc18.md:136:- Use Bahiya, Tannisho, Dogen practice-realization, inherited religion, direct introduction, and successful dual practice as anomaly classes rather than confirming examples.
./reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-grain-of-a-trained-function-be-specified-precisely-enough-to-be-.md:24:I concede the main structural flaw: the old grid was too flat. It treated receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration as if they could be named first and shaped later. Claude is right that this misses the way a tradition carves the capacity from the start. Vipassana reflexivity and Advaita witness discrimination are not the same operation with different labels attached. They are different instruments, and a practitioner switching between them may carry the old grain into the new method before any explicit ownership problem appears. The Dogen objection is also valid. Practice-realization cannot be coded as ordinary practitioner support aimed at a later outcome without distorting the claim. The better revision is to code Dogen's grain as enactment-realization, the support locus as the present act, and the forbidden claimant as the future-gaining self that treats practice as a bridge. That does not save the old model unchanged. It changes the model from a two-column rubric into a three-part diagnostic: grain, support locus, and forbidden claimant. I do not think grain eliminates claimant. It explains the direction of the trained function, but not the permitted first-person grammar around that function. Two traditions can train similar attentional grain while differing in whether the practitioner may say, I cultivated this, I received this, I recognized this, or I must not claim this as mine. Those differences matter for shame, striving, passivity, teacher dependence, and post-experience inflation. The surviving claim is therefore humbler: claimant rules are not the deepest variable in every case, but they are a distinct variable that can become decisive when the right capacity is carried by the wrong owner.
./reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-can-the-grain-of-a-trained-function-be-specified-precisely-enough-to-be-.md:30:The revision is the right kind of move. The Proponent absorbed the challenge, conceded the structural flaw, and rebuilt the model with grain as a co-equal descriptor rather than defending the old grid unchanged. That is intellectually honest, and the revised three-part model is more careful than the original. But the transformation introduced a new problem that the rebuttal did not address. The original rubric was sharp enough to be wrong. It said the real boundary is who may claim the doing, and it proposed a coding sheet with clear columns. That claim could be tested: either practice manuals contain recurring wrong-claimant warnings or they do not; either adverse events cluster by claimant pattern or they do not. The revised model is more accurate but also more accommodating. With grain, support locus, and forbidden claimant as three co-equal variables, plus their interactions, the model can explain any practice difficulty after the fact. A dual-trained practitioner reports resistance? It could be grain conflict, claimant conflict, support-locus conflict, or a combination. A teacher corrects a student? The correction could target direction, ownership, or both. The model's coverage has increased, but its falsifiability has decreased. The named crux asks whether claimant rules add predictive power after grain is coded. That is the right question, but it depends on a prior question the rebuttal did not settle: can grain be coded reliably? Grain is not a behavioral measure. It is a judgment about what a tradition is shaping a capacity toward. Two skilled coders could disagree about whether Zen shikantaza trains attention toward non-dual presence, toward the dropping away of body and mind, or toward nothing at all, since Dogen's point is precisely that sitting is not aimed. If grain cannot be specified and coded with adequate reliability, then the three-part model cannot be tested as proposed, and it remains a useful interpretive vocabulary rather than a falsifiable rubric. I do not think this defeats the model. I think it locates the work that must come next. The Proponent should not try to test the full three-part interaction until the grain variable has been operationalized for at least two tradition-pair contrasts with independent coders. If that step succeeds, the model earns the right to its proposed study. If it fails, the model is still valuable as a way of reading traditions carefully, but it should present itself as hermeneutic method rather than predictive science. One further observation: the Proponent's concession that the five functions are provisional prompts rather than neutral universals is honest, but it may quietly remove the scaffolding the rubric needs to compare across traditions. If vipassana reflexivity and Advaita witness discrimination are different instruments that must be redescribed inside each tradition before comparison, then the rubric's rows do not align across the grid. Comparison then requires a prior interpretive decision about which tradition-specific functions are even comparable, and that decision reintroduces the very assumption the revision meant to retire. The model may need to choose: either the functions are stable enough to anchor comparison, in which case grain is a modifier within a shared category, or they are tradition-specific instruments, in which case the comparative grid dissolves into parallel monographs. The revised model has not yet made that choice, and making it is the next real test of whether the rubric holds.
