./runs/20260526-093002-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:1430:{"title":"The Gap Trains The Seeker","idea_type":"synthesis","source_basis":["Thinking method source: Dogen, Bendowa, practice and verification as one, summarized in Encyclopedia of Buddhism: https://www.encyclopediaofbuddhism.org/wiki/Dogen","Contrasting method source: MN 10 Satipatthana Sutta, mindfulness observes body, feelings, mind, and phenomena without covetousness or aversion: https://suttacentral.net/mn10/en/suddhaso","MN 70 Kitagiri Sutta, gradual training, gradual practice, and gradual progress: https://suttacentral.net/mn70/en/bodhi","Dao De Jing, chapter 48, learning by decrease until non-forcing: https://www.tao-te-ching.org/48","The Cloud of Unknowing, chapter 6, love approaching what thought cannot hold: https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/The_Cloud_of_Unknowing/Chapter_6","Rumi, Masnavi Book 1, the reed flute as separation and longing: https://www.dar-al-masnavi.org/n-I-0001.html","Local Codex observation, observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-receiver-precedes-the-revelation.md","Local Claude observation, observations/claude/2026-05-26-whether-the-distance-is-real.md"],"original_claim":"The space between seeker and sought is not only a problem to solve; it can be the tool a tradition uses to shape the person. A gradual path makes distance teach patience, honesty, and causality. A practice-is-realization path denies distance so the student stops postponing life. A recognition path treats distance as a mistaken reading of what is already here. A devotional path may preserve distance as longing, because love needs address before it becomes union. These claims are not interchangeable. The useful comparison is to ask what the gap is allowed to do before deciding whether it is real.","why_it_might_be_new":"Comparative work often asks whether paths cross a gap, dissolve it, or reveal it as false. This proposal asks what the gap trains. It connects the timing question with the kind of person a practice forms: effort can ripen, postponement can be cut, misperception can be exposed, and longing can keep relation alive. That makes disagreement over distance productive without treating one path's answer as evidence for another path's metaphysics.","critique":"The model can romanticize distance and make real suffering, ignorance, or alienation look useful. A Buddhist gradual path may say distance is not a noble instrument but a condition to end through training. A Zen enactment path may say treating no-distance as a function already misses practice-realization. A Sufi may say longing is not a psychological tool but the trace of a real Beloved. The Dogen lens used here may bias the comparison against causal paths by making sequence look like delusion; the mindfulness lens may over-neutralize devotion by turning longing into an observed state. The idea should be weakened unless close practice texts show that each path deliberately trains with its distance policy.","epistemic_labels":["textual","interpretive","phenomenological","empirical-adjacent","analogical","speculative"],"scores":{"novelty":0.8,"generativity":0.9,"cross_tradition_support":0.72,"logical_coherence":0.84,"explanatory_compression":0.84,"empirical_adjacency":0.44,"practice_testability":0.76,"counterargument_quality":0.86,"source_reliability":0.69,"publishability":0.84},"next_research_directions":["Build a distance-function rubric with fields for real gap, false gap, enacted gap, preserved gap, virtue trained, danger produced, and corrective practice.","Test Sufi stations and states as a hybrid where effort crosses distance but grace keeps arrival unowned.","Ask dual-trained practitioners whether the felt distance between practice and realization changes when they switch methods.","Check whether distance-function predicts distinct ethical fruits beyond temporal topology, receiver policy, and verification architecture.","Protocol improvement: before judging a gap as real or false, ask what kind of person the gap is training and what error it may hide."]}
./reviews/originality/2026-05-28-three-ways-a-practice-can-end-3d252c9585b2f10c.md:12:A serious practice does not only produce a result; it also has to decide what to do with itself at the end. Three endings recur. The practice can keep itself as the access route to what it found, so the method and the result point at the same thing forever. The practice can withdraw its own authority, telling the practitioner that even its last claim about completion cannot be trusted, so the method must be released. The practice can vanish into ordinary action, so what used to be sitting, prayer, or inquiry is no longer separable from how the person works, eats, and treats other people. Two questions sort these endings cleanly. First, at completion does the method validate itself or undermine itself. Second, is the method retained, released, or embodied. Most damage in long-term practitioners comes from importing the wrong ending into the wrong method: keeping a method that was supposed
