./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:762:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-inferential-gap-atman-and-anatta-as-competing-policies-for-objectless-awareness-86683c153f0b6959.md:48:- Nagarjuna, Mulamadhyamakakarika 18.6, https://docslib.org/doc/1736275/mulamadhyamakakarika-by-nagarjuna: overlap: Close anomaly. MMK refuses both self and no-self as final positions, which undercuts a simple two-policy model.; difference: The Claude model treats Madhyamaka as a possible third policy but has not yet integrated it structurally.; novelty impact: Moderate reduction and important revision pressure.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:763:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-inferential-gap-atman-and-anatta-as-competing-policies-for-objectless-awareness-86683c153f0b6959.md:65:- If: Nirodha and deep sleep should become pressure tests for inferential policy. Then: Advaita sources should use continuity, memory, or self-luminosity to defend awareness across apparent absence, while Buddhist sources should explain retrospective knowledge without positing a continuous knower. Weakens if: Either tradition has no stable explanation, or both use the same explanatory rule. Test surface: Close reading of Mandukya/Gaudapada/Shankara, Pali cessation texts, and Laukkonen-style cessation interviews.
