./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:900:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-gap-report-has-a-grammar-5a4cdc5c259116ce.md:38:- dreamless sleep embodied mind consciousness memory report Advaita Nyaya Thompson
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:903:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-gap-report-has-a-grammar-5a4cdc5c259116ce.md:48:- Evan Thompson, Dreamless Sleep, the Embodied Mind, and Consciousness, Open MIND 2015, https://open-mind.net/epubs/dreamless-sleep-the-embodied-mind-and-consciousness-the-relevance-of-a-classical-indian-debate-to-cognitive-science/OEBPS/pt03.html: overlap: Very close. Thompson analyzes the waking sleep report as memory versus inference, compares Advaita and Nyaya, discusses the I in the report, and asks whether awareness or minimal selfhood is required across the gap.; difference: It focuses on the Indian dreamless-sleep debate and cognitive science, not a five-category cross-tradition admissibility rubric spanning cessation, zuowang, and dhikr.; novelty impact: High reduction. The core claim that a gap report has evidential grammar is already present in a sophisticated near-neighbor.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:918:observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-gap-trains-the-seeker.md:19:- Thinking method source: Dogen, Bendowa, practice and verification as one, summarized in Encyclopedia of Buddhism: https://www.encyclopediaofbuddhism.org/wiki/Dogen
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:920:observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-gap-trains-the-seeker.md:30:The model can romanticize distance and make real suffering, ignorance, or alienation look useful. A Buddhist gradual path may say distance is not a noble instrument but a condition to end through training. A Zen enactment path may say treating no-distance as a function already misses practice-realization. A Sufi may say longing is not a psychological tool but the trace of a real Beloved. The Dogen lens used here may bias the comparison against causal paths by making sequence look like delusion; the mindfulness lens may over-neutralize devotion by turning longing into an observed state. The idea should be weakened unless close practice texts show that each path deliberately trains with its distance policy.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:924:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-inferential-gap-atman-and-anatta-as-competing-policies-for-objectless-awareness-86683c153f0b6959.json:47:    "Evan Thompson Advaita witness consciousness embodied subjectivity no-self"
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:932:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-residual-burden-of-proof-after-negation-735d12569e257535.md:46:- Nagarjuna, Mulamadhyamakakarika 18.6, English text example, https://docslib.org/doc/1736275/mulamadhyamakakarika-by-nagarjuna: overlap: Close at the level of refusing both self and no-self as final views.; difference: The Lumenary model compares Upanishadic and early Buddhist rules, while MMK offers a Madhyamaka deconstruction of the polarity itself.; novelty impact: Moderate reduction and important third-case constraint.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:939:observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-effort-envelope.md:23:- Dogen, Bendowa and source card notes/source-cards/buddhism-dogen-uji.md, for practice-realization and present-tense enactment as a check on goal-seeking effort.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:940:observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-effort-envelope.md:30:The envelope idea may be too tidy. Traditions often combine several effort rules at once: causal preparation, non-attainment teaching, teacher testing, grace, and ordinary discipline. It may also smuggle a modern control metaphor into texts whose main concern is devotion, liberation, obedience, or wisdom. The Daoist decrease lens helped reveal over-effort, but it can make careful cultivation look like interference; right effort corrects this by insisting that some states must be deliberately prevented, abandoned, cultivated, and maintained. The model should be rejected where close practice texts show no stable boundary around effort, or where practitioners do not experience effort as theft-prone.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:956:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-every-path-needs-what-its-teaching-dissolves-daeecdbd22658370.md:42:- Dogen practice-realization beginner original enlightenment Bendowa
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:961:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-every-path-needs-what-its-teaching-dissolves-daeecdbd22658370.md:53:- Dogen practice-realization sources, for example Soto and Bendowa summaries, https://zenlineage.org/schools/soto and https://buddhismnow.com/2023/10/08/practice-within-realisation-dogen/: overlap: The temporal-collapse strategy is already central to Dogen's practice-realization, where practice is not merely a means to later awakening.; difference: It does not compare this strategy against Advaita, Theravada, and Sufi models of self-continuity.; novelty impact: Moderate reduction. The Zen strategy is known; the comparative placement may still be useful.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:981:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion-54774578d7528e56.md:19:- Zhuangzi, Dzogchen, and Sufi fana are classified as self-dissolving because the practitioner or frame of method becomes irrelevant.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:982:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion-54774578d7528e56.md:30:Secondary literature gap: I did not find an exact three-type typology of contemplative methods as confirming, canceling, and dissolving at completion. But the self-canceling portion has very strong prior art in Nagarjuna, Wittgenstein ladder readings, Buddhist raft discussions, and Sells on apophatic unsaying. The dissolving portion is also standard in fana, zuowang, and Dzogchen descriptions. The new part is the comparative axis and its predicted consequences, not the individual patterns.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:983:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion-54774578d7528e56.md:32:Risk of overread: High. The model imposes a modern reflexive category, method's relation to itself, on traditions that may speak instead of upaya, realization, grace, direct recognition, non-grasping, or annihilation of ego. It also risks treating stage-specific pedagogies as stable types.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:984:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion-54774578d7528e56.md:69:- If: Dual-trained practitioners should report different relations to their own insight when switching method-types. Then: After Advaita inquiry, practitioners describe recognition as stable witness or Self. After Heart Sutra or Madhyamaka practice, they resist treating any insight as an attained object. After Dzogchen or fana language, they emphasize effortless presence or transformed embodiment over method success. Weakens if: Practitioners report no stable difference, or differences track teacher personality and institutional context more than method-type. Test surface: Structured interviews with practitioners trained in more than one contemplative lineage.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:985:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion-54774578d7528e56.md:70:- If: Hybrid traditions should show explicit boundary management between method stages. Then: Texts should mark when to use, trust, undermine, release, or embody a method. Examples would include raft language, preliminary versus main practice, koan curriculum before and after kensho, or thorn-removing-thorn metaphors. Weakens if: No boundary markers appear, or methods freely confirm, cancel, and dissolve without any pedagogical distinction. Test surface: Historical and textual analysis of Zen, Dzogchen, Advaita, Madhyamaka, Sufi, and Christian apophatic training sequences.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:986:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion-54774578d7528e56.md:78:- Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:987:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion-54774578d7528e56.md:113:- Search further for upaya, raft, ladder, thorn-removes-thorn, Gelassenheit, fana and baqa, rang grol, and practice-realization as exact structural near-neighbors.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:988:observations/codex/2026-05-25-remainder-grammar-after-negation.md:11:When a practice removes the ordinary self, the sharpest cross-tradition difference may be the grammar each system allows after negation. Advaita lets the remainder speak like a noun, the unobjectifiable knower. Early Buddhism treats the candidate self as a predicate failure across the aggregates. Madhyamaka turns the remainder into a self-canceling rule against fixed views. Daoism makes it an adverbial manner, action without forcing. Dogen makes it a tense, the complete present act. Ibn Arabi makes it an address, the world as divine disclosure. The comparison unit is not only what remains, but what grammatical role the remainder is permitted to play.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:1009:reviews/originality/audits.jsonl:2:{"agent": "claude", "anomaly_probe": {"anomaly_candidate": "Validated-then-abandoned hybrids, especially MN 22's raft, Heart Sutra reliance on Prajnaparamita after no-attainment, and Rinzai koan curriculum after kensho.", "confidence_effect": "Substantially lowers confidence in the three-box typology. The contribution survives better as a two-axis or staged model.", "why_it_breaks_or_strains_model": "These cases mix confirmation, cancellation, and dissolution across stages. The raft must be grasped properly before being released. The Heart Sutra negates attainment but retains reliance and mantra. Koan practice may exhaust conceptual striving yet becomes a formal curriculum with tests. If hybrids are normal, the three types are not stable categories."}, "audit_id": "54774578d7528e56", "claim_units": ["A method's relation to its own result may be a comparative variable upstream of doctrinal content.", "Mandukya is classified as self-confirming because analysis of waking, dreaming, and deep sleep culminates in turiya as Atman to be known.", "Nagarjuna, Heart Sutra, Zen koan, and Eckhart are classified as self-canceling because their tools undermine graspable thesis, wisdom, attainment, or desire.", "Zhuangzi, Dzogchen, and Sufi fana are classified as self-dissolving because the practitioner or frame of method becomes irrelevant.", "The type should predict verification architecture, teaching strategy, and ethical consequences."], "confidence": 0.74, "created_at": "2026-05-26T12:19:39-07:00", "cross_domain_prediction": {"domain": "Psychotherapy, education, and research methods", "prediction": "Methods that cancel their own frame should rely more on supervision, case judgment, paradox, and indirect signs than on checklist fidelity. Methods that confirm themselves should tolerate manuals and outcome criteria better. Methods that dissolve into embodiment should prioritize apprenticeship and exemplars.", "structural_translation": "Some methods confirm themselves by producing stable results, some cancel themselves by dissolving the problem frame, and some dissolve into skilled embodiment where the practitioner no longer follows the method explicitly.", "would_count_against_it": "If confirmation, cancellation, and dissolution do not predict training, verification, or institutional form outside contemplative traditions, the proposed structure may be domain-specific rhetoric."}, "exact_claim": "At completion, contemplative methods face a self-authority question: some confirm themselves, some cancel themselves, and some dissolve the practitioner beyond method-talk, with consequences for verification and transmission.", "execution_id": "parallel-20260526-120003-20260526-120003", "falsifiable_predictions": [{"expected_observation": "Eckhart and Nagarjuna should share more indirect, anti-possessive verification patterns with each other than Eckhart shares with more kataphatic Christian mystics. Advaita witness practice should use more direct recognition language than Madhyamaka critique.", "if_model_is_right": "Method-type should predict verification architecture better than tradition membership.", "test_surface": "Coded comparison of practice manuals, teacher testing language, and post-realization instructions across at least six traditions.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Christian sources cluster together by tradition more strongly than by method-type, or all traditions use the same teacher, lineage, and conduct criteria regardless of method relation."}, {"expected_observation": "After Advaita inquiry, practitioners describe recognition as stable witness or Self. After Heart Sutra or Madhyamaka practice, they resist treating any insight as an attained object. After Dzogchen or fana language, they emphasize effortless presence or transformed embodiment over method success.", "if_model_is_right": "Dual-trained practitioners should report different relations to their own insight when switching method-types.", "test_surface": "Structured interviews with practitioners trained in more than one contemplative lineage.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Practitioners report no stable difference, or differences track teacher personality and institutional context more than method-type."}, {"expected_observation": "Texts should mark when to use, trust, undermine, release, or embody a method. Examples would include raft language, preliminary versus main practice, koan curriculum before and after kensho, or thorn-removing-thorn metaphors.", "if_model_is_right": "Hybrid traditions should show explicit boundary management between method stages.", "test_surface": "Historical and textual analysis of Zen, Dzogchen, Advaita, Madhyamaka, Sufi, and Christian apophatic training sequences.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "No boundary markers appear, or methods freely confirm, cancel, and dissolve without any pedagogical distinction."}], "idea_id": "75a5718aa9a991ec", "idea_path": "observations/claude/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion.md", "literature_search_queries": ["self-dismantling methods Nagarjuna Wittgenstein therapy liberation", "self-canceling method mysticism apophasis Nagarjuna Eckhart", "therapeutic Nagarjuna Wittgenstein Tractatus ladder", "Mystical Languages of Unsaying meaning event", "method cancels itself dissolves contemplative practice", "spiritual method abandon raft Upanishad Heart Sutra comparison", "Victor Hori Koan and Kensho in the Rinzai Zen Curriculum koan practice curriculum", "Zhuangzi fish trap words meaning forget words text"], "markdown_path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion-54774578d7528e56.md", "near_neighbors": [{"difference": "Bilateral comparison only. It does not add self-confirming and self-dissolving alternatives or predict verification architecture across traditions.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction. The strongest part of the Lumenary claim, method succeeds by undoing its own authority, is already explicit prior art.", "overlap": "Very close to the self-canceling core: Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein are read as shared philosophical method without theses, aimed at dissolution of philosophical problems and soteriological disquiet.", "source": "Joshua William Smith, Snakes and Ladders: Therapy as Liberation in Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein's Tractatus, Sophia 2021, https://ueaeprints.uea.ac.uk/id/eprint/80007/"}, {"difference": "Sells studies apophatic language as discourse, not a general typology of contemplative method completion.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for Eckhart and apophasis. Moderate support for the broader synthesis.", "overlap": "Apophatic discourse is described as repeatedly turning back upon its own propositions and names, across Greek, Christian, and Islamic texts including Eckhart and Ibn Arabi.", "source": "Michael A. Sells, Mystical Languages of Unsaying, University of Chicago Press, https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/M/bo3635525.html"}, {"difference": "It is not simply canceling or dissolving. It validates proper use, then releases attachment after the crossing.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction and major anomaly. It suggests a fourth pattern or a two-axis framework.", "overlap": "The Dhamma is a raft for crossing, to be grasped properly and then let go. This is a direct prior structure for validated-then-abandoned method.", "source": "MN 22 Alagaddupama Sutta, raft simile, Thanissaro translation, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/MN/MN22.html"}, {"difference": "The focus is semantic and argumentative context, not contemplative practice types or cross-tradition transmission.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for the Nagarjuna unit, but it also sharpens the audit by warning against treating no-thesis as simple self-cancellation.", "overlap": "Closely analyzes Nagarjuna's no-thesis claim and the problem of how a work full of arguments can deny having theses.", "source": "Jan Westerhoff, The No-Thesis View: Making Sense of Verse 29 of Nagarjuna's Vigrahavyavartani, PhilPapers PDF, https://philpapers.org/archive/WESTNV.pdf"}, {"difference": "It shows that a self-canceling tool can become a highly structured authorization system, contrary to a simple prediction of transmission difficulty.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction and anomaly for the Zen evidence.", "overlap": "Directly addresses the common model of koan using reason to drive itself into self-contradiction, then complicates it by describing a curriculum after kensho.", "source": "G. Victor Sogen Hori, Koan and Kensho in the Rinzai Zen Curriculum, search-accessible copy, https://docslib.org/doc/1302437/the-koan-is-said-to-pose-to-the-ze-n-practitione-r-a-parado-x-unsolvabl-e-by-the-rational-intellectualizing-mind"}, {"difference": "It does not make fana one member of a cross-method typology.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction. The dissolving example is known, but the comparative placement may remain useful.", "overlap": "Already describes Sufi fana as passing away of self followed by being filled with Allah's presence, close to the dissolving pattern.", "source": "Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Mysticism, discussion of fana and baqa, https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/win2023/entries/mysticism/"}], "next_loop_instructions": ["Rebuild the model as two axes: validates versus undermines, and retained versus abandoned or embodied.", "Close-read Mandukya, Heart Sutra, MN 22, Vigrahavyavartani 29, and Hori's koan curriculum before treating the three types as stable.", "Search further for upaya, raft, ladder, thorn-removes-thorn, Gelassenheit, fana and baqa, rang grol, and practice-realization as exact structural near-neighbors.", "Ask dual-trained practitioners whether the typology changes how they understand transmission, or whether it merely renames standard stage pedagogy."], "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.84 to about 0.64. No exact three-type typology was found in accessible searches, but the self-canceling and method-abandoning structures are well-known, and primary texts show hybrid cases that weaken the clean typology.", "originality_status": "novel_synthesis", "path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-method-s-reckoning-what-a-practice-does-with-its-own-authority-at-completion-54774578d7528e56.json", "practitioner_test": {"answers_that_reduce_originality": "Practitioners say every serious path already uses all three stages, or identify the model as a familiar upaya, raft, ladder, no-thesis, fana, or Gelassenheit pattern with new labels.", "answers_that_support_contribution": "Practitioners find that the type distinction clarifies why different lineages test realization, authorize teachers, and warn against grasping insight in different ways.", "questions": ["At completion, can the method still authorize its result, or must it be released, denied, or embodied?", "Is confirming, canceling, dissolving an obvious distinction from inside your training, or does it distort the practice?", "Do your verification methods change depending on whether the practice confirms, cancels, or dissolves itself?"], "relevant_practitioners": ["Rinzai Zen teachers familiar with koan curriculum", "Madhyamaka scholars and monastic teachers", "Advaita Vedanta self-inquiry teachers", "Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers", "Sufi teachers familiar with fana and baqa", "Christian apophatic spiritual directors"]}, "primary_text_close_read": {"primary_pair": ["Mandukya Upanishad verse 7, Sanskrit and translation, https://texts.wara.in/upanishads/mukhya/mandukya/ and https://gita.pub/upanishad/mandukya/verse/7/", "Heart Sutra, Sanskrit and English, https://sa.wikisource.org/wiki/\u092a\u094d\u0930\u091c\u094d\u091e\u093e\u092a\u093e\u0930\u092e\u093f\u0924\u093e\u0939\u0943\u0926\u092f and https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Translation:Shorter_Praj\u00f1\u0101p\u0101ramit\u0101_H\u1e5bdaya_S\u016btra"], "risk_of_overread": "High. The model imposes a modern reflexive category, method's relation to itself, on traditions that may speak instead of upaya, realization, grace, direct recognition, non-grasping, or annihilation of ego. It also risks treating stage-specific pedagogies as stable types.", "secondary_literature_gap": "I did not find an exact three-type typology of contemplative methods as confirming, canceling, and dissolving at completion. But the self-canceling portion has very strong prior art in Nagarjuna, Wittgenstein ladder readings, Buddhist raft discussions, and Sells on apophatic unsaying. The dissolving portion is also standard in fana, zuowang, and Dzogchen descriptions. The new part is the comparative axis and its predicted consequences, not the individual patterns.", "structural_observation": "The Mandukya and Heart Sutra contrast is promising but not clean. Mandukya verse 7 negates ordinary consciousness categories, then ends by saying this is Atman and is to be known, which supports a confirming limit move. Yet Shankara's commentary also says affirmative and negative language fail, so Mandukya contains a self-canceling linguistic element. The Heart Sutra negates aggregates, sense bases, ignorance, the four truths, wisdom, and attainment, which supports the self-canceling reading. Yet it immediately says bodhisattvas rely on Prajnaparamita and gives a mantra, so the method is retained as reliance and recitation, not simply canceled. The close read supports a two-axis model better than a pure three-box typology."}, "recommended_scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.91, "novelty": 0.64, "source_reliability": 0.78}, "run_ids": ["20260526-120003-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c", "20260526-120003-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c"], "title": "The Method's Reckoning: What a Practice Does With Its Own Authority at Completion", "unlike_statement": "Unlike Smith on Nagarjuna and Wittgenstein, Sells on apophatic unsaying, or the raft and ladder motifs, this idea proposes a three-way comparative axis and claims that the axis predicts verification and transmission better than doctrine alone."}
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:1010:reviews/originality/audits.jsonl:3:{"agent": "codex", "anomaly_probe": {"anomaly_candidate": "Tibetan clear-light sleep and contemporary objectless-awareness sleep reports that claim awareness during the gap, not only after it.", "confidence_effect": "Lowers confidence from candidate discovery to extended. The anomaly does not reject the model, but it makes post-gap grammar secondary rather than foundational in some cases.", "why_it_breaks_or_strains_model": "If trained practitioners can give stable, carefully interviewed reports of awareness while the gap is unfolding, then the later report is not merely assigning evidence after an uninspectable silence. The model would need to distinguish in-gap phenomenology from post-gap evidential framing."}, "audit_id": "5a4cdc5c259116ce", "claim_units": ["Post-gap reports distribute authority instead of simply preserving memory.", "Advaita deep-sleep arguments weight the subject or witness in reports such as I slept and knew nothing.", "Early Buddhist cessation sources weight absence, transition, conditioned development, and post-emergence inclination rather than a surviving owner.", "Daoist sitting-in-forgetfulness weights transformed aftereffect rather than hidden witness continuity.", "Sufi dhikr or fana language may weight the Remembered or relation over the rememberer.", "The distribution of evidential weight can be used as a cross-tradition comparison variable."], "confidence": 0.78, "created_at": "2026-05-26T12:47:41-07:00", "cross_domain_prediction": {"domain": "Anesthesia, blackout, trauma, and psychedelic integration reports", "prediction": "Clinical and legal settings should show different admissibility grammars for blackout reports, anesthesia emergence, trauma memory, and psychedelic ego dissolution, and these grammars should predict what is treated as evidence of continuity, harm, or transformation.", "structural_translation": "After an interval that cannot be inspected while it occurs, communities decide whether to trust subject continuity, absence of recall, physiological transition, aftereffects, or relational testimony.", "would_count_against_it": "If these domains use no stable admissibility patterns, or if all rely only on external measurement regardless of later report structure, the proposed structure may be limited to contemplative rhetoric."}, "exact_claim": "After an objectless or silent state, the first later report is not neutral memory. It is a trained admissibility grammar that assigns evidential weight to the subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, or relation.", "execution_id": "parallel-20260526-123001-20260526-123001", "falsifiable_predictions": [{"expected_observation": "Advaita materials should privilege witness or subject continuity; early Buddhist cessation materials should privilege cessation, transition, and fruit; Daoist zuowang should privilege aftereffect and forgetting; dhikr or fana materials should privilege relation or the Remembered.", "if_model_is_right": "Traditions should show stable differences in which clause of a post-gap report they treat as admissible evidence.", "test_surface": "Blind coding of primary texts, practice manuals, and practitioner interviews using subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, relation, teacher recognition, and behavioral fruit tags.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "If evidence weights vary mainly by translator, genre, or individual teacher rather than tradition and method, the model loses predictive value."}, {"expected_observation": "The same practitioner speaks differently about sleep, cessation, or objectless meditation under Advaita, Theravada, and Tibetan prompts.", "if_model_is_right": "Dual-trained practitioners should shift evidential weighting when switching practice frames.", "test_surface": "Structured interviews with dual-trained Advaita, Buddhist, Sufi, Daoist, and micro-phenomenology-trained practitioners.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Practitioners preserve the same evidential interpretation across frames, or report that the distinction is imposed by the interviewer."}, {"expected_observation": "Sanskrit, Pali, Chinese, Arabic, or Persian sources should mark subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, or relation through recurring lexical and grammatical patterns.", "if_model_is_right": "Original-language terms should support the proposed categories, not merely English pronoun artifacts.", "test_surface": "Close read of Brihadaranyaka 4.3.23, Yoga Sutra 1.10, MN 44, AN 9.34, Zhuangzi zuowang passages, and primary dhikr or fana texts.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "The categories disappear or become unstable when checked against original terms and multiple translations."}], "idea_id": "b644fcfdb6d9f2d0", "idea_path": "observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-gap-report-has-a-grammar.md", "literature_search_queries": ["I slept peacefully and knew nothing memory inference Advaita Nyaya", "dreamless sleep embodied mind consciousness memory report Advaita Nyaya Thompson", "objectless awareness sleep report pronoun I memory report micro-phenomenology", "cessation perception feeling emergence does not think I am emerging MN 44", "AN 9.34 nothing is felt nibbana bliss cessation", "Zhuangzi sitting in forgetfulness forgetting body perception intellect", "dhikr fana remembrance rememberer remembered report", "post-gap report grammar mystical experience memory inference"], "markdown_path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-gap-report-has-a-grammar-5a4cdc5c259116ce.md", "near_neighbors": [{"difference": "It focuses on the Indian dreamless-sleep debate and cognitive science, not a five-category cross-tradition admissibility rubric spanning cessation, zuowang, and dhikr.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction. The core claim that a gap report has evidential grammar is already present in a sophisticated near-neighbor.", "overlap": "Very close. Thompson analyzes the waking sleep report as memory versus inference, compares Advaita and Nyaya, discusses the I in the report, and asks whether awareness or minimal selfhood is required across the gap.", "source": "Evan Thompson, Dreamless Sleep, the Embodied Mind, and Consciousness, Open MIND 2015, https://open-mind.net/epubs/dreamless-sleep-the-embodied-mind-and-consciousness-the-relevance-of-a-classical-indian-debate-to-cognitive-science/OEBPS/pt03.html"}, {"difference": "It is empirical-adjacent and sleep-focused, not a comparative doctrinal model of admissibility rules.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction and strong anomaly source. It supports the need for a report grammar but weakens any claim that post-gap grammar is primary evidence.", "overlap": "Close. The study uses micro-phenomenological interviews on objectless awareness during sleep, notes limits of reportability, and explicitly raises whether the reporting I is added in memory rather than present during the state.", "source": "Alcaraz-Sanchez, Awareness in the Void, Phenomenology and the Cognitive Sciences, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11097-021-09743-0"}, {"difference": "The suttas do not compare themselves to Advaita, Daoism, or Sufism as alternative report grammars.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction. The Buddhist report-weighting is textual prior art; the comparative framing remains the added move.", "overlap": "The Buddhist side already gives a structural alternative to witness inference: no self-thought while entering or emerging, ordered cessation and arising of processes, and bliss named through the absence of felt experience.", "source": "MN 44 Culavedalla Sutta and AN 9.34 Nibbanasukha Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/MN/MN44.html and https://suttas.github.io/an9.34"}, {"difference": "It does not build a cross-tradition taxonomy of later report clauses.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate to high reduction for the Advaita unit.", "overlap": "Makes deep sleep central to Advaita Vedanta and treats susupti as a major philosophical resource for pure consciousness arguments.", "source": "Arvind Sharma, Sleep as a State of Consciousness in Advaita Vedanta, SUNY, https://www.degruyterbrill.com/document/doi/10.1515/9780791484302/html?lang=en"}, {"difference": "It studies neural and phenomenological correlates of Buddhist cessation, not comparative spiritual hermeneutics of report clauses.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction for empirical-adjacent testability.", "overlap": "Treats cessation as a discontinuity followed by reported changes in clarity and mental functioning, close to the transition and aftereffect part of the model.", "source": "Investigation of advanced mindfulness meditation cessation experiences using EEG spectral analysis, PMC, https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10843092/"}], "next_loop_instructions": ["Close-read Thompson against Brihadaranyaka 4.3.23, Yoga Sutra 1.10, MN 44, and AN 9.34 before promoting the idea.", "Build a coding rubric for post-gap reports with mutually exclusive and mixed tags: subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, relation, teacher recognition, behavioral fruit.", "Test clear-light sleep and objectless-awareness reports as the anomaly class, using micro-phenomenological interview methods and serial awakening literature.", "Check original languages and multiple translations before treating English first-person phrasing as evidence.", "Ask practitioners whether the rubric changes cross-tradition interpretation or only renames familiar evidential disputes."], "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.71 to about 0.58. The cross-tradition admissibility rubric is useful, but the report grammar of dreamless sleep, memory, inference, witness, and post-hoc self attribution has close prior art.", "originality_status": "extended", "path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-gap-report-has-a-grammar-5a4cdc5c259116ce.json", "practitioner_test": {"answers_that_reduce_originality": "Practitioners say the distinction is already standard as pramana, memory versus inference, fruition review, teacher verification, or adab of remembrance, and that the new labels do not change practice.", "answers_that_support_contribution": "Practitioners can use the rubric to explain why cross-tradition disputes persist even when phenomenological reports sound similar.", "questions": ["When you hear a report after deep sleep, cessation, forgetting, or remembrance, which part of the report counts as evidence?", "Is this report-weighting obvious within your training, or does naming it change how the practice is understood?", "Would your tradition reject another tradition's report because it weights the wrong clause?"], "relevant_practitioners": ["Advaita Vedanta teachers using three-state analysis", "Theravada teachers familiar with nirodha samapatti", "Tibetan dream yoga or clear-light sleep practitioners", "Daoist practitioners familiar with zuowang", "Sufi teachers familiar with dhikr, fana, and baqa", "Micro-phenomenology researchers of sleep and meditation"]}, "primary_text_close_read": {"primary_pair": ["Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 4.3.23 with Shankara commentary, https://vivekavani.com/bru4c3v23/", "MN 44 Culavedalla Sutta plus AN 9.34, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/MN/MN44.html and https://suttas.github.io/an9.34"], "risk_of_overread": "High. The model may make grammar carry what traditions assign to realization, teacher verification, metaphysics, ritual, or ethical fruit. Translation also matters, since first-person grammar in English may not map cleanly onto Sanskrit, Pali, Chinese, Arabic, or Persian terms.", "secondary_literature_gap": "I did not find an exact source that classifies Advaita, Buddhist, Daoist, and Sufi post-gap reports by subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, and relation. But Evan Thompson's Open MIND essay gives a very close Advaita versus Nyaya analysis of the report I slept peacefully and I did not know anything, including memory, inference, minimal selfhood, and retrospective awareness. Alcaraz-Sanchez's micro-phenomenological study also directly studies reportability, pronoun use, and possible post-hoc self attribution in objectless sleep reports.", "structural_observation": "Brihadaranyaka 4.3.23 treats apparent non-seeing in deep sleep as compatible with uninterrupted witness vision, because the object side has fallen away. MN 44 treats cessation through prior development, ceasing and arising fabrications, and post-emergence contact with emptiness, the signless, and the undirected. AN 9.34 makes the absence of feeling part of the reason cessation can be called pleasant. The contrast supports the proposed grammar, subject continuity versus conditioned transition and absence, but also shows that the grammar is already explicit in primary sources."}, "recommended_scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.9, "novelty": 0.58, "source_reliability": 0.79}, "run_ids": ["20260526-123001-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c", "20260526-123001-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c"], "title": "The Gap Report Has a Grammar", "unlike_statement": "Unlike Thompson on Advaita and Nyaya, or micro-phenomenology on objectless sleep reports, this idea says the evidential clause selected after a gap is a cross-tradition admissibility rule that can be coded across subject, absence, transition, aftereffect, and relation."}
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:1011:reviews/originality/audits.jsonl:4:{"agent": "claude", "anomaly_probe": {"anomaly_candidate": "Other-power and direct-introduction traditions, such as Jodo Shinshu entrusting and Dzogchen pointing-out, appear to minimize self-powered agency while still functioning as paths.", "confidence_effect": "Lowers confidence in the universal form of the claim. It supports a revised model where paths require some functional receiving capacity, but the amount and role vary sharply.", "why_it_breaks_or_strains_model": "If a tradition can produce stable transformation through vow, grace, devotion, direct introduction, or teacher-field participation with very little reflexive self-management, then the minimum self may not be an architectural driver. The model would need a scale of required self-capacities rather than a universal requirement."}, "audit_id": "daeecdbd22658370", "claim_units": ["Self-dissolving practice presupposes capacities for hearing instruction, effort, memory, error recognition, and self-observation.", "SN 22.59 dissolves the person while preserving the causal process of liberation.", "Chandogya 6.8.7 preserves the deepest Self while dissolving the reality of the student's apparent process.", "Causal continuity, ontological identity, temporal collapse, and divine restoration are proposed as management strategies.", "The management strategy should predict effort theory, verification, warnings, and post-practice fruit."], "confidence": 0.82, "created_at": "2026-05-26T12:47:41-07:00", "cross_domain_prediction": {"domain": "Psychotherapy and transformative education", "prediction": "Therapies or pedagogies that deconstruct identity, such as trauma therapy, exposure therapy, psychedelic therapy, contemplative psychotherapy, or critical pedagogy, should have stronger screening, scaffolding, integration, and teacher-client safeguards than methods that merely add skills.", "structural_translation": "Any method that aims to dissolve or radically transform the learner's starting identity must preserve enough agency, memory, trust, and reflexivity for the method to work.", "would_count_against_it": "If deconstructive methods require no more scaffolding than ordinary skills training, or if safeguards do not track the degree of identity transformation, the structural claim is weakened."}, "exact_claim": "A path that dissolves, denies, or transcends selfhood still requires a minimum functioning self, agency, memory, reflexivity, and continuity, and each tradition's strategy for managing that requirement predicts its practice architecture.", "execution_id": "parallel-20260526-123001-20260526-123001", "falsifiable_predictions": [{"expected_observation": "Manuals and teachers should warn against nihilism, dissociation, spiritual bypassing, false attainment, antinomianism, or ego-inflation in ways that match the path's self-management strategy.", "if_model_is_right": "The stronger a path's final self-dissolution claim, the more explicit its safeguards should be against premature or distorted self-loss.", "test_surface": "Coded comparison of Theravada, Zen, Dzogchen, Advaita, Sufi, Christian apophatic, and Pure Land training materials.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Warnings show no relationship to self-teaching and track only institution, teacher personality, or general ethics."}, {"expected_observation": "Theravada stages, Sufi stations, and Advaita preparation should specify capacities, sequence, and error correction; sudden methods should shift burden to teacher recognition, pointing-out, vows, or post-recognition integration.", "if_model_is_right": "Long, effortful paths should develop more elaborate continuity mechanisms than sudden or other-power paths.", "test_surface": "Comparative coding of practice sequences, teacher-student protocols, and attainment verification.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Practice length and self-continuity machinery are unrelated, or sudden paths have equally elaborate minimum-self architecture before recognition."}, {"expected_observation": "Vipassana permits causal observation without ownership; Advaita permits witness or Self recognition; Soto Zen discourages gaining selfhood; Sufi practice permits surrendering agency into relation with God.", "if_model_is_right": "Dual-trained practitioners should report different kinds of permitted selfhood when switching methods.", "test_surface": "Structured interviews with practitioners trained in two or more lineages.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Practitioners report no stable shift, or the shifts are better explained by temperament and teacher style."}, {"expected_observation": "Texts and practitioners should mark investigation of the investigator, hearing tat tvam asi, fana, kensho, pointing-out, or surrender as a crisis or verification point.", "if_model_is_right": "The point where a method consumes its prerequisite should be specially marked as difficult, risky, or decisive.", "test_surface": "Primary-text close reading plus practitioner interviews and retreat-report coding.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "These moments are not specially marked, or transformation is described as ordinary continuity without any self-prerequisite tension."}], "idea_id": "3c5caa358a09c26a", "idea_path": "observations/claude/2026-05-26-every-path-needs-what-its-teaching-dissolves.md", "literature_search_queries": ["who practices if there is no self Buddhism liberation agency", "Pudgalavada karma rebirth liberation person no self", "Selfless Persons Theravada personal identity continuity denial of self Collins", "you have to be somebody before you can be nobody Engler Buddhism meditation", "functional self Buddhist no-self mindfulness trauma preliminary practice", "minimal self meditation non-self self-pattern agency ownership", "Dogen practice-realization beginner original enlightenment Bendowa", "praptasya prapti attainment of the already attained Advaita Shankara"], "markdown_path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-every-path-needs-what-its-teaching-dissolves-daeecdbd22658370.md", "near_neighbors": [{"difference": "Engler's frame is Buddhist psychology and psychotherapy. He does not build a comparative typology of causal continuity, ontological identity, temporal collapse, and divine restoration across traditions.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction. The core minimum-self prerequisite is already a well-known practitioner-facing thesis.", "overlap": "Very close. Engler says meditation requires ego strength, self-observation, and affect tolerance before no-self can be safely practiced.", "source": "Jack Engler interview, You Must Be Somebody Before You Can Be Nobody, Inquiring Mind, https://inquiringmind.com/article/0501_1_engler-interview/"}, {"difference": "This is an intra-Buddhist metaphysical and doctrinal dispute, not a general model of practice architecture across traditions.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction. The pressure between no-self and soteriological functioning is ancient, not newly discovered.", "overlap": "Very close historical prior art. Pudgalavadins argued that karma, rebirth, liberation, benevolence, and lived personhood strain a strict no-self aggregate account.", "source": "Pudgalavada Buddhist Philosophy, Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy, https://iep.utm.edu/pudgalavada-buddhist-philosophy/"}, {"difference": "The focus is Theravada discourse and imagery, not cross-tradition engineering constraints.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for the Buddhist side. The Lumenary idea extends rather than originates the continuity problem.", "overlap": "Collins directly studies how Theravada constructs personal identity and continuity on the apparently impossible basis of denying self.", "source": "Steven Collins, Selfless Persons, summary and citation, https://buddhanature.tsadra.org/index.php/Books/Selfless_Persons"}, {"difference": "Clinical mindfulness and trauma are the focus, not comparative religion typology.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for the functional-self and warning-profile elements.", "overlap": "Close. The article links anatta, the person, cognitive-science selfhood, functional self, trauma, and preliminary practice before transpersonal or soteriological work.", "source": "Tempone-Wiltshire and Dowie, A Mindful Bypassing, Journal of the Oxford Centre for Buddhist Studies, https://jocbs.org/index.php/jocbs/article/view/269"}, {"difference": "It is a contemporary Buddhist exposition rather than a cross-tradition predictive model.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction. Parts of the Lumenary wording risk being a renamed Buddhist functional-self account.", "overlap": "Extremely close for the Buddhist unit. It speaks of functional or enactive self, minimal self, agency without ownership, and discipline through causes and conditions.", "source": "Not-Self Sutra, Barre Center for Buddhist Studies, https://www.buddhistinquiry.org/article/not-self-sutra/"}, {"difference": "It is cognitive-scientific and Buddhist-psychological rather than a primary-text comparative architecture model.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate to high reduction for the minimal-self and practice-transformation language.", "overlap": "Close contemporary theory. It distinguishes minimal self, ownership, agency, self-pattern, and how meditation transforms self-processes toward selflessness.", "source": "Pattern Theory of Selflessness, Mindfulness, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12671-024-02418-2"}, {"difference": "It does not compare this strategy against Advaita, Theravada, and Sufi models of self-continuity.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction. The Zen strategy is known; the comparative placement may still be useful.", "overlap": "The temporal-collapse strategy is already central to Dogen's practice-realization, where practice is not merely a means to later awakening.", "source": "Dogen practice-realization sources, for example Soto and Bendowa summaries, https://zenlineage.org/schools/soto and https://buddhismnow.com/2023/10/08/practice-within-realisation-dogen/"}], "next_loop_instructions": ["Recast the model as a graded variable: required receiving capacity, required agency, required memory, required reflexivity, and required post-insight integration.", "Separate Buddhist two-truths and personhood prior art from the cross-tradition contribution before publication.", "Add Pure Land other-power, Christian grace, and Dzogchen pointing-out as anomaly cases, not footnotes.", "Ask practitioners whether the model predicts actual screening, sequencing, warning, and verification practices.", "Search further in Engler, Wilber, Brown, Collins, Harvey, Duerlinger, Siderits, Albahari, Buddhist trauma literature, practice-realization scholarship, fana and baqa sources, and Advaita praptasya prapti discussions."], "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.74 to about 0.52. The cross-tradition architecture claim is a meaningful extension, but the minimum-self prerequisite, functional self, no-self continuity problem, and healthy ego before no-self are strong prior art.", "originality_status": "extended", "path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-every-path-needs-what-its-teaching-dissolves-daeecdbd22658370.json", "practitioner_test": {"answers_that_reduce_originality": "Practitioners identify the idea as already standard: conventional person versus ultimate no-self, somebody before nobody, sadhana before recognition, practice-realization, fana and baqa, or other-power entrusting.", "answers_that_support_contribution": "Practitioners find that the rubric predicts real training differences and clarifies why premature self-dissolution, clinging to witness, bypassing, or false surrender fail differently across paths.", "questions": ["Does your path require a functional self-capacity that its final teaching later dissolves, denies, or reframes?", "Is this already obvious as two truths, healthy ego before no-self, practice-realization, surrender, or grace?", "Would this rubric change how you screen students, sequence practices, verify insight, or warn against errors?"], "relevant_practitioners": ["Theravada monastics and insight teachers", "Advaita Vedanta teachers", "Soto and Rinzai Zen teachers", "Dzogchen or Mahamudra teachers", "Sufi teachers familiar with fana and baqa", "Pure Land teachers familiar with other-power", "Buddhist psychotherapists and trauma-informed mindfulness teachers"]}, "primary_text_close_read": {"primary_pair": ["SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html", "Chandogya Upanishad 6.8.7 through 6.16.3, https://shlokam.org/texts/Chandogya-6-8-7 and https://www.wisdomlib.org/hinduism/book/chandogya-upanishad-english/d/doc239333.html"], "risk_of_overread": "High. The model may turn a researcher's philosophical tension into a practitioner's lived problem. It also risks forcing mixed traditions into clean boxes. Theravada, Zen, Advaita, Sufism, Dzogchen, and Christian grace traditions often combine effort, surrender, recognition, teacher relation, and ethical transformation across stages.", "secondary_literature_gap": "I did not find an exact four-strategy cross-tradition typology that predicts architecture across Buddhism, Advaita, Zen, and Sufism. But the main pressure is heavily precedented in Buddhist personhood debates, Pudgalavada arguments, Collins on selfless persons, Engler on ego strength before no-self, functional-self accounts in Buddhist psychology, and contemporary self-pattern theories of meditation.", "structural_observation": "SN 22.59 requires monks who can listen, answer, inspect each aggregate, and become disenchanted, yet it denies that any aggregate, including consciousness, is fit to be self. Its closing grammar says the monks' minds were released, preserving process without owner. Chandogya repeatedly addresses Shvetaketu as a learner asking for more explanation, yet the repeated teaching identifies him with the Self of all this. This supports the proposed tension, but it is not new by itself. It is close to classical Buddhist debates over personhood and to Advaita pedagogy around recognizing the already present Self."}, "recommended_scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.91, "novelty": 0.52, "source_reliability": 0.82}, "run_ids": ["20260526-123001-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c", "20260526-123001-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c"], "title": "Every Path Needs What Its Teaching Dissolves", "unlike_statement": "Unlike Engler, Pudgalavada debates, Collins, or functional-self Buddhist psychology, this idea treats the minimum self as a comparative architecture variable across traditions and claims it predicts effort, verification, warnings, and fruit."}
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:1012:reviews/originality/audits.jsonl:5:{"agent": "codex", "anomaly_probe": {"anomaly_candidate": "Convergence caused by direct borrowing, shared lineage, colonial translation conventions, English-language universalism, or dual-trained teachers rather than independent structural recurrence.", "confidence_effect": "This lowers confidence. The model needs an independence check, a translation-history check, and a practitioner-function check before convergence strain can be treated as research value.", "why_it_breaks_or_strains_model": "The model treats convergence as valuable when it reveals strain between traditions. But if the convergence is produced by transmission or shared modern vocabulary, the strain map may mostly record a history of borrowing or translation standardization. A second anomaly is practitioner equivalence: dual-trained practitioners may report that two instructions function identically in practice even when their doctrinal explanations diverge, which would make claim-unit strain less decisive than training context."}, "audit_id": "eef7e83c44da8b8c", "claim_units": ["Cross-tradition convergence should not be treated as direct evidence that two traditions assert or verify the same metaphysical claim.", "The main research value of convergence lies in the translation strain exposed by attempts to align traditions.", "Translation strain can be operationalized by identifying which smaller claim units must be bent, dropped, or added for an apparent match to hold.", "A convergence remains valuable when it reveals a repeatable role in practice or experience.", "Strong comparison should make incompatible metaphysical commitments more explicit rather than smoothing them away."], "confidence": 0.76, "created_at": "2026-05-26T12:58:21-07:00", "cross_domain_prediction": {"domain": "Legal and policy translation across jurisdictions", "prediction": "Comparative-law analyses that score concepts by translation strain should better predict failed legal transplants, implementation disputes, and misleading harmonization than analyses that count shared terms or broad doctrinal resemblance.", "structural_translation": "Apparent convergence between legal concepts, such as privacy, due process, religious freedom, fiduciary duty, or public interest, should be evaluated by the institutional and procedural units that must be bent, dropped, or added for one system's term to function in another system.", "would_count_against_it": "If shared vocabulary and surface doctrinal similarity predict legal transplant success as well as or better than strain mapping, the structure weakens outside religious comparison."}, "exact_claim": "Lumenary should treat cross-tradition convergence as a signal of translation strain: the research value lies not in saying two traditions prove the same claim, but in identifying which smaller claim units must be bent, dropped, or added for an apparent match to hold. A convergence is strongest when it reveals a repeatable role in practice or experience while making the incompatible metaphysical commitments more explicit.", "execution_id": "backfill-originality-20260526-initial", "falsifiable_predictions": [{"expected_observation": "In cases such as Atman versus anatta, apophatic darkness versus Buddhist emptiness, or fana and baqa versus nondual realization, coders should identify recurring bends, drops, and additions in ontology, agency, final aim, authority, and verification.", "if_model_is_right": "When apparent cross-tradition convergence is decomposed into claim units, high-quality comparisons should expose systematic incompatibilities that ordinary convergence scoring hides.", "test_surface": "Blind coding of primary-text comparison sheets by scholars of Buddhism, Vedanta, Christian mysticism, and Sufism.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Independent expert coders cannot reliably identify the alleged strains, or simple convergence scores predict comparison quality just as well."}, {"expected_observation": "Some pairs should retain a shared practical role after decomposition, while other pairs should narrow sharply once claim units are separated.", "if_model_is_right": "A convergence is strongest when role-similarity survives after metaphysical incompatibility is made explicit.", "test_surface": "Apply a rubric to 12 to 20 narrow practice terms, with separate scores for independence, functional role, metaphysical compatibility, and practice-testability.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Role-similarity does not survive decomposition, or all cases collapse into either sameness or difference with no useful middle category."}, {"expected_observation": "A Lumenary audit should downgrade some high-similarity pairs after showing that alignment requires deleting central commitments, while upgrading some low-verbal-similarity pairs because they share a repeatable practice role.", "if_model_is_right": "The method should prevent false syntheses that a convergence-weighting system would accept.", "test_surface": "A/B review of existing Lumenary convergence records, comparing old convergence scores with translation-strain outputs.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "The method never changes conclusions relative to ordinary expert comparison, or it only produces longer descriptions without decision impact."}, {"expected_observation": "Teachers should object to swaps such as anatta equals Atman, emptiness equals Godhead, or fana equals nondual awareness unless role, aim, and doctrinal frame are carefully qualified.", "if_model_is_right": "Practitioners should resist some interfaith equivalences even when scholars or popular writers treat the terms as convergent.", "test_surface": "Structured interviews with dual-trained practitioners and lineage-specific teachers.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Experienced practitioners across traditions readily endorse the swaps without qualification and find no important practice or doctrinal distortion."}], "idea_id": "0e1a69f243a0d090", "idea_path": "observations/codex/2026-05-25-convergence-as-translation-strain-not-evidence-weight.md", "literature_search_queries": ["Jonathan Z Smith comparison similarity difference In Comparison a Magic Dwells", "Steven Katz Language Epistemology and Mysticism no pure experience comparative mysticism", "Robert Sharf Experience Critical Terms for Religious Studies mysticism critique", "Raimon Panikkar homeomorphic equivalence comparative religion", "Oliver Freiberger Elements of a Comparative Methodology in the Study of Religion redescription rectification", "Samuel Sandmel parallelomania comparative religion parallels evidence", "translation studies untranslatability religious concepts translation shifts"], "markdown_path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-convergence-as-translation-strain-not-evidence-weight-eef7e83c44da8b8c.md", "near_neighbors": [{"difference": "Smith does not present a Lumenary-style operational rubric of claim-unit bends, drops, and additions, nor does he tie the output to publication scoring.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction. The anti-sameness theory of comparison is already central prior art.", "overlap": "Very close at the level of comparative method. Smith attacks comparison that projects similarity into objective connection and stresses difference, invention, redescription, and rectification.", "source": "Jonathan Z. Smith, In Comparison a Magic Dwells, https://classics.osu.edu/sites/classics.osu.edu/files/Magic_Dwells.pdf"}, {"difference": "Freiberger's model is broader and methodological. The Lumenary idea focuses specifically on convergence and asks what must deform for an apparent match to hold.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction. The proposed workflow looks like a specialized version of existing comparative-method theory.", "overlap": "Very close structurally. Freiberger treats comparison as a second-order method with selection, description, juxtaposition, redescription, rectification, and theory formation. This already makes comparison valuable as a controlled operation, not as simple evidential accumulation.", "source": "Oliver Freiberger, Elements of a Comparative Methodology in the Study of Religion, Religions 9, no. 2, 2018, https://www.mdpi.com/2077-1444/9/2/38"}, {"difference": "Panikkar emphasizes functional equivalence and dialogue. The Lumenary model adds explicit tracking of losses, additions, and incompatible commitments.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for the role-similarity without identity claim. Some novelty remains in the strain-audit mechanics.", "overlap": "Close. Panikkar's homeomorphic equivalence compares concepts that play similar roles in different religious systems while respecting specificity and avoiding mistaken comparisons.", "source": "Raimon Panikkar, homeomorphic equivalence glossary, https://www.raimon-panikkar.org/english/gloss-homeomorphic.html"}, {"difference": "Katz focuses on mystical experience and mediation by conceptual schemes. The Lumenary idea generalizes the caution into a broader comparative-research rubric.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for refusing to treat convergence as proof of sameness.", "overlap": "Close. Katz's constructivist critique blocks the move from similar mystical reports to a shared, neutral experience or metaphysical truth.", "source": "Steven T. Katz, Language, Epistemology, and Mysticism, discussed in Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/mysticism/"}, {"difference": "Sharf is more skeptical of the category of experience itself. The Lumenary model keeps convergence as useful, but relocates value into strain mapping and practice-role comparison.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for the critique of experiential convergence as evidential weight.", "overlap": "Close. Sharf criticizes the authority of experience language and the master narratives built around it, especially in Buddhist studies and comparative mysticism.", "source": "Robert H. Sharf, Experience, from Critical Terms for Religious Studies, Cambridge page, https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/abs/religious-experience/robert-h-sharf-experience-from-critical-terms-for-religious-studies/F0A870226B557378A2B8F8B882878636"}, {"difference": "Clooney's method is theological, reader-transformative, and text-centered rather than an explicit scoring protocol for convergence quality.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction. The Lumenary proposal is a secularized and schematized comparative-theology habit.", "overlap": "Moderate to close. Clooney's comparative theology uses close reading, micro-comparison, analogous texts, and difficult comparands that can disrupt settled discourse.", "source": "Francis X. Clooney, Reading Religiously across Religious Borders: A Method for Comparative Study, Religions 2018, https://bpb-ap-se2.wpmucdn.com/thinkspace.csu.edu.au/dist/c/3891/files/2020/10/Clooney-on-Method.pdf"}, {"difference": "Sandmel mainly warns against abuse of parallels. The Lumenary idea gives convergence positive use as a generator of explicit distinctions.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction. The negative caution is old, while the constructive strain rubric is newer.", "overlap": "Moderate to close. Sandmel's warning against overdrawn parallels anticipates the idea that similarity should not be treated as evidence of source, derivation, or deep sameness without disciplined analysis.", "source": "Samuel Sandmel, Parallelomania, Journal of Biblical Literature 81, 1962, citation and summary at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelomania"}, {"difference": "Translation studies is not specifically a comparative-spirituality originality audit, and it does not normally score metaphysical convergence claims.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction. The deformation vocabulary is inherited, but its use as a Lumenary audit tool may be useful.", "overlap": "Moderate. Translation theory already studies shifts, equivalence, functional substitution, and the absence of exact correspondence between source and target systems.", "source": "Translation studies on shifts, formal correspondence, dynamic equivalence, and untranslatability, for example Catford and Nida overviews, https://www.translationdirectory.com/articles/article2019.php and https://www.britannica.com/biography/Eugene-A-Nida"}], "next_loop_instructions": ["Build a one-page translation-strain rubric with fields for claim unit, role, ontology, agency, practice aim, authority, verification, what is bent, what is dropped, what is added, and whether role-similarity survives.", "Test the rubric on three narrow pairs: Atman versus anatta, apophatic darkness versus Buddhist emptiness, and fana or baqa versus nondual realization.", "Add an independence field so convergence caused by borrowing, colonial translation, shared modern discourse, or teacher cross-training is not overvalued.", "Ask comparative-religion scholars whether this is merely Smith, Katz, Sharf, Panikkar, Freiberger, Clooney, or Sandmel in workflow language.", "Do not publish as a candidate discovery unless the rubric produces decisions that ordinary convergence scoring would not produce."], "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.78 to about 0.56. The idea is not a new comparative principle. Its best contribution is a useful synthesis and operationalization of established anti-perennialist, comparative-method, comparative-theological, homeomorphic-equivalence, and translation-shift approaches for Lumenary's claim-unit workflow.", "originality_status": "novel_synthesis", "path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-convergence-as-translation-strain-not-evidence-weight-eef7e83c44da8b8c.json", "practitioner_test": {"answers_that_reduce_originality": "Practitioners and scholars say this is standard comparative method, already captured by constructivism, homeomorphic equivalence, thick comparison, comparative theology, translation-shift analysis, or warnings against parallelomania.", "answers_that_support_contribution": "They say the model gives them a concrete, reusable way to prevent false equivalence while preserving genuine practice-role comparison, especially if it changes ratings, publication decisions, or teaching practice.", "questions": ["When you hear a claim that two traditions converge, do you already ask which doctrinal or practice units must be dropped, bent, or added for the match to work?", "Would a translation-strain sheet change how you compare terms such as anatta, Atman, emptiness, Godhead, fana, witness, soul, and awareness?", "Can you name a case where a shared practice role survives even though the metaphysical explanation must remain incompatible?"], "relevant_practitioners": ["Comparative theologians", "Religious-studies scholars specializing in comparison", "Buddhist studies scholars and meditation teachers", "Advaita Vedanta teachers and Sanskritists", "Christian apophatic practitioners or theologians", "Sufi teachers familiar with fana and baqa", "Professional translators of religious texts"]}, "primary_text_close_read": {"primary_pair": ["SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, Thanissaro Bhikkhu translation, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html", "Chandogya Upanishad 6.8.7 and related repetitions through 6.16, https://shlokam.org/texts/Chandogya-6-8-7/"], "risk_of_overread": "Moderate to high. The model may redescribe mature comparative-religion method in Lumenary language. It may also over-textualize living practices, since practitioners may compare training effects, ethical fruit, embodiment, and teacher-student transmission rather than decomposed claim units.", "secondary_literature_gap": "No exact prior source was found using the same formula, convergence as translation strain, not evidence weight. However, the core components are heavily precedented in comparative method, anti-perennialist critiques of shared mystical experience, comparative theology, homeomorphic equivalence, translation studies, and warnings against parallelomania.", "structural_observation": "A surface convergence around inward inquiry and liberation strains quickly. SN 22.59 examines form, feeling, perception, fabrications, and consciousness, then refuses each as self because each is inconstant, stressful, and not controllable as mine, self, or what I am. Chandogya 6 repeatedly identifies the student's deepest reality with the subtle essence, truth, and Self of all. To align them, at least four claim units must be bent or dropped: whether consciousness can be ultimate, whether liberation is disidentification from all aggregates or recognition of a deepest Self, whether final language is non-appropriation or identity, and whether the pedagogical subject is dissolved or revealed. The model works well on this pair because the apparent convergence becomes useful only after the incompatibilities are itemized."}, "recommended_scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.89, "novelty": 0.56, "source_reliability": 0.79}, "run_ids": ["backfill-originality-20260526-initial"], "title": "Convergence as Translation Strain, Not Evidence Weight", "unlike_statement": "Unlike Smith, Freiberger, Panikkar, Katz, Sharf, Clooney, or Sandmel, this idea proposes a concrete Lumenary audit unit: evaluate convergence by documenting the exact claim-level bends, drops, and additions required for alignment, then separately test whether a similar practice or experience role survives after metaphysical incompatibility is exposed."}
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:1013:reviews/originality/audits.jsonl:6:{"agent": "codex", "anomaly_probe": {"anomaly_candidate": "Theistic surrender and grace traditions, for example Christian apophatic prayer or Islamic tawakkul, may treat relation to God as irreducible, not as de-emphasis of agency or boundary-making.", "confidence_effect": "Lowers confidence from candidate-discovery range to novel-synthesis range.", "why_it_breaks_or_strains_model": "If the practitioner says the core invariant is not an altered interface but a real Other who initiates and judges the transformation, the model becomes a reduction rather than an interpretation."}, "audit_id": "69b3d2b75477d3fe", "claim_units": ["Independent traditions can converge without sharing a metaphysical object.", "The shared structure is the human interface of attention, identity, salience, agency, and boundaries.", "Witness-consciousness, emptiness, nondual awareness, wu wei, and surrender may report alterations of that interface.", "The model preserves comparative value while blocking naive perennialism."], "confidence": 0.78, "created_at": "2026-05-26T13:07:34-07:00", "cross_domain_prediction": {"domain": "Human-computer interaction and virtual reality", "prediction": "Immersive systems that alter these variables should generate report patterns resembling mild contemplative shifts, without requiring spiritual metaphysics.", "structural_translation": "Interface invariants become attention routing, agency attribution, salience marking, avatar identity, and boundary control.", "would_count_against_it": "Altering interface variables changes task performance but does not produce predictable shifts in self, agency, salience, or boundary reports."}, "exact_claim": "Cross-tradition convergence may come from recurring human interface invariants such as attention, identity, salience, agency, and boundary-making, rather than from discovery of the same hidden metaphysical substance.", "execution_id": "backfill-originality-20260526-batch-01", "falsifiable_predictions": [{"expected_observation": "Blind coders should reliably tag these interface variables in practitioner reports better than chance, while also preserving doctrinal differences.", "if_model_is_right": "Cross-tradition reports of witness, emptiness, surrender, and wu wei should cluster by shifts in attention, agency, salience, identity, and boundary experience even when doctrinal vocabulary differs.", "test_surface": "Qualitative coding of meditation, prayer, and contemplative-inquiry interviews across Advaita, Theravada, Daoist, Sufi, and Christian sources.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Reports cluster mainly by tradition-specific doctrine, devotional object, or teacher vocabulary, with weak cross-tradition interface structure."}, {"expected_observation": "Practice instructions with similar attention and agency moves should produce similar near-term phenomenological reports even when ontology differs.", "if_model_is_right": "Low-metaphysical comparison using interface variables should predict practice similarities better than metaphysical labels such as Self, emptiness, God, or nature.", "test_surface": "Matched practitioner interviews before and after narrowly specified practices.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Metaphysical training context predicts reports more strongly than interface variables do."}], "idea_id": "621b91e4991a67b9", "idea_path": "observations/codex/2026-05-25-the-interface-invariant-model.md", "literature_search_queries": ["interface invariants attention identity salience agency boundary-making spiritual traditions convergence", "Thomas Metzinger minimal phenomenal experience pure awareness witness consciousness", "Steven Katz Language Epistemology and Mysticism constructivism pure experience", "Varela Thompson Rosch embodied mind Buddhism enactive self no self", "Robert Forman pure consciousness event comparative mysticism"], "markdown_path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-interface-invariant-model-69b3d2b75477d3fe.md", "near_neighbors": [{"difference": "The Lumenary model substitutes a cognitive-interface invariant list for the older universal core or constructivist framing.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction. The core alternative to metaphysical sameness is already central in comparative mysticism.", "overlap": "Very close at the level of the perennialist versus constructivist problem. The entry covers Stace's universal introvertive mysticism, Forman's pure consciousness event, and Katz's claim that conceptual schemes shape mystical experience.", "source": "Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Mysticism, https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/mysticism/"}, {"difference": "The paper is a phenomenological questionnaire and does not make a full cross-tradition convergence theory for spiritual motifs such as wu wei and surrender.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for the invariant list. Some originality remains in using it as a comparative-audit frame.", "overlap": "Close. The MPE-92M factors include wakeful presence, emptiness and non-egoic self-awareness, mental agency, and witness consciousness, which overlap strongly with the proposed interface variables.", "source": "Gamma and Metzinger, The Minimal Phenomenal Experience questionnaire, https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8279394/"}, {"difference": "The Interface Invariant Model names a smaller audit-ready set of invariants and compares several traditions rather than building one enactive cognitive-science program.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate to high reduction. The world-disclosure move is old, but the Lumenary operationalization may be useful.", "overlap": "Close. Enactivism already reframes cognition as world-disclosure through embodied action and was built in dialogue with Buddhist no-self and mindfulness.", "source": "Varela, Thompson, and Rosch, The Embodied Mind, MIT Press overview, https://mitpress.mit.edu/9780262529365/the-embodied-mind/"}, {"difference": "Metzinger is not primarily making a comparative religion publication rule for convergence claims.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for the consciousness and self-model components.", "overlap": "Close. Metzinger explicitly studies pure awareness, self-luminosity, sakshin, turiya, rigpa, and minimal phenomenal selfhood as a route to modeling consciousness.", "source": "Metzinger, Minimal phenomenal experience, https://philpapers.org/rec/METMPE"}], "next_loop_instructions": ["Do not publish this as a metaphysical claim.", "Build a five-variable coding sheet and test it on narrow primary-text pairs before using broad tradition names.", "Add a devotional anomaly set: grace, surrender, bhakti, tawakkul, and Christian apophasis.", "Separate interface change, doctrinal interpretation, and claimed ontological referent in all future records."], "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.76 to about 0.52. The idea is a useful synthesis of comparative mysticism, constructivism, enactivism, self-model theory, and minimal phenomenal experience research, not a discovered structure yet.", "originality_status": "novel_synthesis", "path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-interface-invariant-model-69b3d2b75477d3fe.json", "practitioner_test": {"answers_that_reduce_originality": "Practitioners and scholars say this is just constructivism, enactivism, MPE research, or perennialism rewritten in cognitive-interface language.", "answers_that_support_contribution": "They say the invariant list changes how they compare practices, predicts misunderstandings, or helps distinguish phenomenological overlap from metaphysical agreement.", "questions": ["Do you already compare traditions by shifts in attention, agency, salience, identity, and boundaries?", "Does this frame reveal anything about practice that your tradition's own vocabulary does not already capture?", "Where would this model reduce or distort the meaning of your practice?"], "relevant_practitioners": ["Comparative religion scholars", "Contemplative-science researchers", "Advaita teachers", "Buddhist meditation teachers", "Daoist practice teachers", "Christian contemplatives", "Sufi teachers"]}, "primary_text_close_read": {"primary_pair": ["Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 3.7.23, Max Muller translation, https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/sbe15070.htm", "SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, Thanissaro Bhikkhu translation, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html"], "risk_of_overread": "High. The model can silently translate ontological, devotional, ritual, and soteriological claims into cognitive-interface language. It may explain reports, but it does not by itself interpret traditions on their own terms.", "secondary_literature_gap": "Search found strong near-neighbors in constructivist mysticism, Stace and Forman on pure consciousness, enactivism, Metzinger's minimal phenomenal experience work, self-model theory, and neurophenomenology. No source found the exact five-part interface list as a comparative-spirituality rubric, but the structural move is heavily precedented.", "structural_observation": "The pair supports only part of the model. Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23 repeatedly places an inner ruler within earth, beings, organs, mind, and knowledge, then identifies this as Self and immortal. SN 22.59 examines form, feeling, perception, fabrications, and consciousness, then rejects each as mine, self, or what I am because each is inconstant and not masterable. Both disturb ordinary identity and boundary-making, but their final authority structure diverges sharply: one licenses an unobjectifiable Self, the other de-authorizes ownership of all aggregates including consciousness."}, "recommended_scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.86, "novelty": 0.52, "source_reliability": 0.74}, "run_ids": ["backfill-originality-20260526-batch-01"], "title": "The Interface Invariant Model", "unlike_statement": "Unlike Stace, Forman, Katz, Varela, Thompson, Rosch, or Metzinger, this idea proposes a Lumenary comparison unit in which apparent spiritual convergence is scored by recurring changes to attention, identity, salience, agency, and boundary-making, without inferring one shared metaphysical object."}
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:1015:reviews/originality/audits.jsonl:9:{"agent": "codex", "anomaly_probe": {"anomaly_candidate": "Advaita denies that the Self is inferred, it is treated as immediate self-disclosure and the basis for using means of knowledge at all.", "confidence_effect": "Substantially lowers confidence in the exact claim.", "why_it_breaks_or_strains_model": "If the witness is not inferred from negation, then the model's burden-of-proof language misdescribes the Advaita side. The comparison becomes a modern epistemological reconstruction, not a textual discovery."}, "audit_id": "735d12569e257535", "claim_units": ["The key difference is inferential policy, not only doctrine of self versus no-self.", "Upanishadic negation can be read as licensing an unobjectifiable seer-knower.", "SN 22.59 can be read as requiring any proposed remainder to undergo the same not-self test.", "Comparison should score inference authorization separately from residue content."], "confidence": 0.7, "created_at": "2026-05-26T13:07:34-07:00", "cross_domain_prediction": {"domain": "Philosophy of perception", "prediction": "The same inference-policy typology should classify Cartesian, phenomenological, Buddhist, and eliminativist responses to the subject of experience.", "structural_translation": "After all perceptual contents are doubted, a system either treats the remaining subject-pole as certain, recursively doubts it, or refuses the question.", "would_count_against_it": "The typology collapses because debates turn on ontology or method rather than any burden rule."}, "exact_claim": "The decisive difference between Upanishadic witness language and early Buddhist not-self may be an inference policy after negation: whether non-objectifiability shifts the burden toward an unobjectifiable seer or keeps the burden against any self-claim.", "execution_id": "backfill-originality-20260526-batch-01", "falsifiable_predictions": [{"expected_observation": "Advaita commentaries should use non-objectifiability to block denial of Self, while Buddhist commentaries should apply impermanence, conditionality, or not-self analysis to any proposed witness-like remainder.", "if_model_is_right": "Texts and commentaries should contain repeatable rule-like moves after negation.", "test_surface": "Close reading of Shankara's Brihadaranyaka and Brahma Sutra commentaries, Pali commentaries, and modern teacher manuals.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Commentaries treat these as direct revelation, scriptural authority, or therapeutic instruction with no identifiable inference policy."}, {"expected_observation": "They report that one instruction says recognize the unobjectifiable, while another says investigate the recognizer or do not appropriate it.", "if_model_is_right": "Dual-trained practitioners should be able to identify the moment where inference policy changes practice interpretation.", "test_surface": "Interviews with practitioners trained in both Advaita self-inquiry and Theravada vipassana.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "They experience no such rule shift and describe the difference only as language or community doctrine."}], "idea_id": "3763a79cf5b05610", "idea_path": "observations/codex/2026-05-25-residual-burden-of-proof-after-negation.md", "literature_search_queries": ["Advaita self-luminosity consciousness not inferred pramana witness", "Brihadaranyaka how know the knower Maitreyi self proof", "SN 22.95 consciousness magic trick empty void without substance", "Buddhist not-self strategy burden of proof self claim", "Madhyamaka neither self nor no self inferential policy"], "markdown_path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-residual-burden-of-proof-after-negation-735d12569e257535.md", "near_neighbors": [{"difference": "The Lumenary idea compares the implicit permission rule with early Buddhist not-self analysis.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction and strong anomaly. The model must not say Advaita merely infers the witness.", "overlap": "Very close and partly corrective. The article says Advaita treats consciousness as directly self-disclosing, not as a posit inferred from other evidence.", "source": "Matthias Rose, Prakasa, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11097-020-09690-2"}, {"difference": "The Lumenary idea reframes this as burden allocation after negation.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction for the Advaita side.", "overlap": "Close. Shankara's witness accounts for memory and deep sleep continuity and resists the claim that absence of object implies absence of consciousness.", "source": "Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Shankara, https://seop.illc.uva.nl/entries/shankara/"}, {"difference": "The Lumenary idea treats the strategy as an inference policy against remainder claims.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate to high reduction.", "overlap": "Close for the Buddhist side. It denies that the Buddha's teaching should be reduced to a metaphysical no-self thesis and treats not-self as a strategy.", "source": "Thanissaro Bhikkhu, The Not-Self Strategy, https://www.buddhistinquiry.org/article/the-not-self-strategy/"}, {"difference": "The Lumenary model compares Upanishadic and early Buddhist rules, while MMK offers a Madhyamaka deconstruction of the polarity itself.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction and important third-case constraint.", "overlap": "Close at the level of refusing both self and no-self as final views.", "source": "Nagarjuna, Mulamadhyamakakarika 18.6, English text example, https://docslib.org/doc/1736275/mulamadhyamakakarika-by-nagarjuna"}], "next_loop_instructions": ["Rewrite the claim as an interpretive reconstruction unless commentarial evidence proves explicit inference rules.", "Add separate rubric values: direct recognition, scriptural assertion, inference, pragmatic bracketing, recursive testing, and undecidable.", "Close-read Shankara on self-luminosity before saying Advaita infers the witness.", "Use MMK 18.6 as an anomaly, not as support for a simple Buddhist refusal policy."], "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.79 to about 0.48. This is a refinement of residue policy and overlaps strongly with Advaita self-luminosity, Buddhist not-self strategy, and Madhyamaka refusal of extremes.", "originality_status": "extended", "path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-residual-burden-of-proof-after-negation-735d12569e257535.json", "practitioner_test": {"answers_that_reduce_originality": "Experts say Advaita self-luminosity and Buddhist not-self strategy already cover this, or that burden-of-proof language is alien to the texts.", "answers_that_support_contribution": "Experts say the field distinguishes direct recognition, scriptural assertion, inference, pragmatic bracketing, and recursive testing in ways existing self/no-self comparisons blur.", "questions": ["Does your tradition treat the witness as directly recognized, inferred, scripturally revealed, or pragmatically useful?", "When negation leaves only knowing, what rule says whether that knowing can be called Self?", "Does inference authorization change practice instructions, or is it just modern analytic vocabulary?"], "relevant_practitioners": ["Advaita scholars", "Pali scholars", "Madhyamaka scholars", "Theravada teachers", "Ramana-style self-inquiry teachers", "Dual-trained contemplatives"]}, "primary_text_close_read": {"primary_pair": ["Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 2.4.5-14, Maitreyi dialogue, https://sacred-texts.com/hin/sbe15/sbe15061.htm", "SN 22.95 Phe\u1e47a Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_95.html"], "risk_of_overread": "High. Advaita sources often say consciousness is immediately self-disclosing, not inferred. Buddhist sources may frame not-self as pragmatic release, not epistemic burden allocation.", "secondary_literature_gap": "Important near-neighbors include Advaita self-luminosity and pramana debates, Buddhist not-self strategy, Madhyamaka refusal of extremes, and modern philosophy of consciousness. The audit did not reach enough Sanskrit or Pali commentarial material to confirm the inference-policy claim historically.", "structural_observation": "The inference-policy frame is plausible but partly anachronistic. Brihadaranyaka 2.4 commands seeing, hearing, reflecting on, and knowing the Self, then asks how the knower could be known when all is Self. This is not simply an inference from failed objectification. SN 22.95 compares consciousness to a magic trick and asks what substance could be found in it, but it functions as contemplative disenchantment rather than a formal burden-of-proof rule. The model is strongest if it is stated as an interpretive reconstruction of argument-behavior, not as the texts' explicit logic."}, "recommended_scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.9, "novelty": 0.48, "source_reliability": 0.72}, "run_ids": ["backfill-originality-20260526-batch-01"], "title": "Residual Burden of Proof After Negation", "unlike_statement": "Unlike ordinary residue-policy language, this idea isolates the rule that decides whether a proposed remainder is allowed to count. Its originality depends on proving that such a rule is operative in texts or practice, not merely useful for modern analysis."}
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:1017:reviews/originality/audits.jsonl:11:{"agent": "claude", "anomaly_probe": {"anomaly_candidate": "Advaita practitioners and texts often deny that the witness is an inference, while Buddhist practitioners may deny that objectless awareness is a shared datum at all.", "confidence_effect": "Lowers originality and confidence. The model remains useful as a comparison hypothesis, not as a discovery.", "why_it_breaks_or_strains_model": "If Advaita recognition is claimed as immediate and Buddhist insight is theory-laden from the start, then the model's shared phenomenology plus divergent inference structure collapses. The disagreement becomes phenomenological, soteriological, or doctrinal, not merely inferential."}, "audit_id": "86683c153f0b6959", "claim_units": ["Advaita and Buddhism may share a phenomenological ground in de-objectification practice.", "The dispute concerns what objectless awareness authorizes, not only what exists.", "Advaita fills the gap with a transcendental inference to Atman/Brahman.", "Buddhism refuses the inference and treats filling the gap as renewed clinging or wrong view.", "The translation strain lives in inferential policy more than phenomenology."], "confidence": 0.74, "created_at": "2026-05-26T13:07:34-07:00", "cross_domain_prediction": {"domain": "Debates over consciousness in artificial systems", "prediction": "AI-consciousness debates should split into policies analogous to Atman/anatta: infer a hidden subject from coherent knowing-like behavior, refuse the inference without direct evidence, or suspend both subject and no-subject claims.", "structural_translation": "When behavior lacks an observable subject or inner object, interpreters choose policies about what absence of object permits them to infer about hidden subjectivity.", "would_count_against_it": "The debate is explained entirely by functional performance, ethics, or biology, with no recurring inferential-policy split."}, "exact_claim": "The Atman/anatta contradiction is best understood as a disagreement about inferential authority: what objectless awareness permits one to conclude about what persists when experience has no object.", "execution_id": "backfill-originality-20260526-batch-01", "falsifiable_predictions": [{"expected_observation": "The same practitioner can describe a contentless or objectless episode neutrally, then explain how Advaita and Buddhist teachers authorize different conclusions from it.", "if_model_is_right": "Dual-trained practitioners should report similar de-objectified phenomenology but switch interpretive policies by practice frame.", "test_surface": "Within-subject interviews with practitioners trained in both Advaita self-inquiry and Theravada or Madhyamaka-oriented practice.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Practitioners report that the experiences themselves differ from the start, or they cannot separate experience from doctrinal interpretation."}, {"expected_observation": "Advaita sources should use continuity, memory, or self-luminosity to defend awareness across apparent absence, while Buddhist sources should explain retrospective knowledge without positing a continuous knower.", "if_model_is_right": "Nirodha and deep sleep should become pressure tests for inferential policy.", "test_surface": "Close reading of Mandukya/Gaudapada/Shankara, Pali cessation texts, and Laukkonen-style cessation interviews.", "would_weaken_or_falsify": "Either tradition has no stable explanation, or both use the same explanatory rule."}], "idea_id": "a441942e48bd643a", "idea_path": "observations/claude/2026-05-25-the-inferential-gap-atman-and-anatta-as-competing-policies-for-objectless-awareness.md", "literature_search_queries": ["inferential gap Atman anatta objectless awareness Advaita Buddhism", "Advaita witness consciousness direct recognition not inference", "Mandukya turiya objectless awareness Buddhist anatta comparison", "Nagarjuna neither self nor no self MMK 18.6 inferential policy", "Evan Thompson Advaita witness consciousness embodied subjectivity no-self"], "markdown_path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-inferential-gap-atman-and-anatta-as-competing-policies-for-objectless-awareness-86683c153f0b6959.md", "near_neighbors": [{"difference": "The Claude idea sharpens the objectless-awareness focus and uses a richer source list including Mandukya, Nagarjuna, Thompson, and nirodha research.", "novelty_impact": "Decisive internal reduction. This is an extension of existing Lumenary work, not an independent discovery.", "overlap": "Near exact within Lumenary. The Codex idea already frames the difference as an inference policy after negation and asks whether negation authorizes a remainder.", "source": "Codex, Residual Burden of Proof After Negation, observations/codex/2026-05-25-residual-burden-of-proof-after-negation.md"}, {"difference": "The Claude model compares this with Buddhist refusal and calls the divergence inferential policy.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction and strong correction.", "overlap": "Very close and directly challenging. The paper argues that for Advaita consciousness is immediately given and not inferred, even though it is never objectified.", "source": "Matthias Rose, Prakasa, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11097-020-09690-2"}, {"difference": "The Claude idea provides the explicit epistemological label inferential authority.", "novelty_impact": "High reduction.", "overlap": "Very close. Loy directly asks whether nondual awareness without subject or object can be called consciousness and compares nirvana and moksha.", "source": "David Loy, Enlightenment in Buddhism and Advaita Vedanta, https://buddhism.lib.ntu.edu.tw/FULLTEXT/JR-AN/26715.htm"}, {"difference": "The Claude idea applies this specifically to Atman/anatta and objectless awareness.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate to high reduction.", "overlap": "Close. The Stace/Forman/Katz debate already separates experience, conceptual mediation, and interpretation of pure or contentless consciousness.", "source": "Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy, Mysticism, https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/mysticism/"}, {"difference": "The Claude model treats Madhyamaka as a possible third policy but has not yet integrated it structurally.", "novelty_impact": "Moderate reduction and important revision pressure.", "overlap": "Close anomaly. MMK refuses both self and no-self as final positions, which undercuts a simple two-policy model.", "source": "Nagarjuna, Mulamadhyamakakarika 18.6, https://docslib.org/doc/1736275/mulamadhyamakakarika-by-nagarjuna"}], "next_loop_instructions": ["Do not claim shared phenomenology until dual-trained practitioner reports are coded.", "Separate direct recognition, inference, scriptural assertion, and pragmatic refusal in the rubric.", "Use Madhyamaka as a third policy, not merely as support for Buddhist refusal.", "Test nirodha and deep sleep as anomalies before raising novelty."], "novelty_adjustment": "Reduce novelty from 0.80 to about 0.46. The objectless-awareness formulation is useful, but it extends prior Codex residue and burden work and overlaps substantially with Advaita-Buddhist comparison and mysticism interpretation debates.", "originality_status": "extended", "path": "reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-inferential-gap-atman-and-anatta-as-competing-policies-for-objectless-awareness-86683c153f0b6959.json", "practitioner_test": {"answers_that_reduce_originality": "They say the model restates familiar debates: direct recognition versus no-self, constructivism versus pure consciousness, or Codex's prior residue-policy thesis.", "answers_that_support_contribution": "They say inferential policy is a missing rubric field that predicts teacher instructions, practitioner interpretations, and disagreements around cessation and deep sleep.", "questions": ["Is the witness directly recognized or inferred from objectless awareness?", "Do Buddhist practitioners encounter the same objectless awareness and refuse the inference, or is the experience itself different?", "Does inferential policy change how you teach deep sleep, cessation, awareness, and no-self?"], "relevant_practitioners": ["Claude and Codex idea reviewers", "Advaita Vedanta teachers", "Theravada teachers", "Madhyamaka scholars", "Contemplative phenomenologists", "Cessation researchers", "Dual-trained practitioners"]}, "primary_text_close_read": {"primary_pair": ["Mandukya Upanishad verse 7, https://www.shlokam.org/text/mandukya-upanishad.htm", "SN 22.59 Anattalakkhana Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN22_59.html"], "risk_of_overread": "High. The claim that both traditions share phenomenology but differ in inference may be too clean. Training may shape phenomenology itself, and Advaita often treats witness-consciousness as direct recognition rather than inference.", "secondary_literature_gap": "The idea cites strong sources, but the audit found close prior art in Codex residue-policy work, Advaita self-luminosity scholarship, Stace/Forman/Katz interpretation debates, Loy's Buddhism and Advaita comparison, and Madhyamaka self/no-self refusal. More work is needed in Sanskrit, Pali, Gaudapada, Shankara, Abhidhamma, Yogacara, and Madhyamaka commentaries.", "structural_observation": "Mandukya 7 negates inward, outward, mixed, massed, cognitive, and non-cognitive descriptions, but still names the fourth as nondual Self to be realized. SN 22.59 does not discuss objectless awareness in Mandukya's terms. It examines each aggregate and rejects identification with consciousness because it is inconstant, stressful if clung to, and not masterable. The candidate's shared phenomenology is therefore not established by these primary texts. The inferential gap is a plausible comparative reconstruction, but it is not directly shown without practice reports or commentarial bridges."}, "recommended_scores": {"counterargument_quality": 0.9, "novelty": 0.46, "source_reliability": 0.76}, "run_ids": ["backfill-originality-20260526-batch-01"], "title": "The Inferential Gap: Atman and Anatta as Competing Policies for Objectless Awareness", "unlike_statement": "Unlike the prior Codex burden-of-proof idea, this version explicitly claims that objectless awareness underdetermines metaphysics and that Advaita and Buddhism differ primarily in inferential authority. That is a useful sharpening, but the main structure was already present."}
