./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:2139:observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-effort-envelope.md:30:The envelope idea may be too tidy. Traditions often combine several effort rules at once: causal preparation, non-attainment teaching, teacher testing, grace, and ordinary discipline. It may also smuggle a modern control metaphor into texts whose main concern is devotion, liberation, obedience, or wisdom. The Daoist decrease lens helped reveal over-effort, but it can make careful cultivation look like interference; right effort corrects this by insisting that some states must be deliberately prevented, abandoned, cultivated, and maintained. The model should be rejected where close practice texts show no stable boundary around effort, or where practitioners do not experience effort as theft-prone.
./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/codex-cli.stderr.log:2176:reviews/originality/2026-05-26-convergence-as-translation-strain-not-evidence-weight-eef7e83c44da8b8c.md:69:- If: When apparent cross-tradition convergence is decomposed into claim units, high-quality comparisons should expose systematic incompatibilities that ordinary convergence scoring hides. Then: In cases such as Atman versus anatta, apophatic darkness versus Buddhist emptiness, or fana and baqa versus nondual realization, coders should identify recurring bends, drops, and additions in ontology, agency, final aim, authority, and verification. Weakens if: Independent expert coders cannot reliably identify the alleged strains, or simple convergence scores predict comparison quality just as well. Test surface: Blind coding of primary-text comparison sheets by scholars of Buddhism, Vedanta, Christian mysticism, and Sufism.
